<HEAD>Voters Decide Congressional Runoff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A businessman defeated a city planner Tuesday in a Republican primary runoff for the right to challenge Democratic Rep. <PERSON> George </PERSON> `` Buddy'' <PERSON> Darden </PERSON>, while a late-breaking campaign financing controversy complicated another state race. According to unofficial returns from all 207 precincts, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Lamutt </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Cobb </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> had 6,220 votes, or 52 percent, to 5,691, or 48 percent, for <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Johns </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Roswell </LOCATION> planner. The two were the surviving candidates for the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION>'s 7th District nomination after the primary election three weeks ago. The race was thrown into a runoff when neither could claim a majority. <PERSON> Darden </PERSON> was unopposed in the Democratic congressional primary. In <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>'s only statewide primary runoff, former state Sen. <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> won the Democratic nomination for a seat on the utility-regulating <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Tuesday after a bitter fight with state Rep. <PERSON> Cathey </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>. According to unofficial returns from 2,290 of the 2,569 precincts, <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> had 216,321, or 55 percent, to Ms. <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>'s 176,175, or 45 percent While polls were still open, a transcript unsealed in federal court indicated <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> supervisors and managers were pressured to make contributions to <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON>. Utility officials said that would violate `` a very important policy'' of the company, and <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> called the allegations `` reckless and unfounded.'' In a mid-evening telephone interview after the contest appeared concluded, <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> refused to say he would decline future contributions from sources with power company interests. `` If I go on the commission, we ought to talk about what we're going to do about this,'' he said `` I should n't try to stand out as an island by myself.'' Ms. <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> said, `` I'm not going to win; the utilities are going to win. My opponent beat me to death with a money bag.'' She said <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> distorted her legislative record in ads aired throughout the state and described the campaign as `` very nasty.''
