<HEAD>`Nightmare' Remains At Top</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The latest `` Nightmare on Elm Street'' movie retained first place in box office revenues last weekend, while `` Betrayed,'' about white supremacists in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, made its debut in second place. `` Nightmare on Elm Street 4: The Dream Master'' earned $ 6.9 million last weekend. `` Betrayed,'' the Costa-Gavras directed thriller, took in more than $ 5.5 million. Two other movies made debuts in the top 10, with `` Stealing Home'' coming in ninth and `` Hot To Trot'' finishing 10th. `` A Fish Called Wanda'' moved to third place from fourth last week, earning $ 3.7 million. `` Die Hard'' was fourth with $ 3.66 million, and has earned $ 52 million so far as the summer's solid action-adventure film. `` Young Guns'' dropped from last week's second place to fifth place this week with $ 3.62 million. Disney's `` Who Framed Roger Rabbit'' reached a new plateau in earnings last weekend. Its $ 2.98 million, good for sixth place, brought its total to $ 124.6 million, making it the second-highest grossing Disney movie. Last year's `` Three Men and A Baby,'' from <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION>'s Touchstone division, earned $ 167.4 million. In seventh place was `` Cocktail'' with $ 2.92 million, followed by `` Married To The Mob'' with $ 2.4 million. `` Stealing Home'' was good for $ 2.3 million and ninth place, with `` Hot to Trot'' earning $ 2.2 million for 10th place. `` The Last Temptation of Christ,'' in its third week of release, was on 48 screens compared with 18 in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> last week, with ticket sales for the Universal movie at $ 561,631 for the weekend and $ 11,701 per screen. The movie, which has spurred protests from some Christians, has so far grossed $ 2.6 million. Here are the top films for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor Relations, with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater screens, average per screen, total gross and number of weeks in release. 1. `` Nightmare On Elm Street 4: The Dream Master,'' New Line, $ 6.9 million, 1,767 screens, $ 3,955 per screen, $ 25 million, two weeks. 2. `` Betrayed,'' <ORGANIZATION> MGM-UA </ORGANIZATION>, $ 5.5 million, 1,036 screens, $ 5,342 per screen, $ 5.5 million, one week. 3. `` A Fish Called Wanda,'' <ORGANIZATION> MGM-UA </ORGANIZATION>, $ 3.7 million, 1,223 screens, $ 3,083 per screen, $ 30.7 million, seven weeks. 4. `` Die Hard,'' 20th Century <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>, $ 3.66 million, 1,432 screens, $ 2,561 per screen, $ 52 million, seven weeks. 5. `` Young Guns,'' 20th <ORGANIZATION> Century </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fox </ORGANIZATION>, $ 3.62 million, 1,371 screens, $ 2,645 per screen, $ 22.9 million, three weeks. 6. `` Who Framed <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabbit </PERSON>,'' Disney, $ 2.98 million, 1,549 screens, $ 1,924 per screen, $ 124.6 million, 10 weeks. 7. `` Cocktail,'' <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION>, $ 2.92 million, 1,339 screens, $ 2,185 per screen, $ 51.4 million, five weeks. 8. `` Married to the Mob,'' <ORGANIZATION> Orion </ORGANIZATION>, $ 2.4 million, 826 screens, $ 2,907 per screen, $ 7.4 million, two weeks. 9. `` Stealing Home,'' <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros. </ORGANIZATION>, $ 2.3 million, 984 screens, $ 2,385 per screen, $ 2.3 million, one week. 10. `` Hot To Trot,'' <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros. </ORGANIZATION>, $ 2.2 million, 1,056 screens, $ 2,089 per screen, $ 2.2 million, one week.
