<HEAD>Air Force Seeks Cuts in Shuttle Launch Witnesses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> says safety concerns prompted its request that <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> cut back drastically on the number of people allowed on a close-in press site to cover next month's launch of space shuttle Discovery. In the past, there have been as many as 3,500 people on the press mound during a launch at <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canaveral </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheehan </PERSON>, chief spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> already has processed 2,600 news media applications for the Discovery launch. <PERSON> Sheehan </PERSON> declined to specify the number the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> wants to allow, but the number circulating around the <ORGANIZATION> Kennedy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> is 100 _ including <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> public affairs personnel. Those excluded would be allowed back onto the press site soon after the shuttle lifts off. As discussions with the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> continued, top <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> managers met Monday and decided not to set a specific launch date until after a detailed preparedness review on Sept. 13-14. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> has been working toward a liftoff of the first post-Challenger mission in the last week of September. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>, which has jurisdiction over safety at <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s Kennedy facility, is worried about flying shrapnel should one of the solid rocket boosters explode `` They are asking us ` what are the minimum numbers you can have there and still be able to operate effectively?''' <PERSON> Sheehan </PERSON> said. He said 6,000 to 7,000 space center workers not involved with the shuttle on the pad also might be barred for some period preceding launches. The press site and <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s huge vehicle assembly building are 4.2 miles from pad 34-B. Reporters have been there for every launch beginning with the Apollo program in 1967. `` They have some real basis for concern,'' <PERSON> Sheehan </PERSON> said. `` It came about because of what they learned after the Challenger -LRB- accident -RRB- and what they learned from the Atlas that had to be destroyed. `` What they learned is you ca n't predict where it's going to go. It can go down, it can go forward, it can go up.'' After the Challenger shuttle was engulfed in flames 73 seconds after liftoff on Jan. 28, 1986, killing its crew of seven, the Challenger's booster rockets careened about over the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> for another minute before they were destroyed by a command from the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> safety officer. In March 1987, an Atlas Centaur rocket had to be destroyed 51 seconds into its flight when it started to tumble. No one on the ground was injured in either incident. Before Challenger, <PERSON> Sheehan </PERSON> said, engineers assumed the booster rockets would continue on the same path if they were released during flight, perhaps tumbling. `` The detonation of the <ORGANIZATION> SRB </ORGANIZATION> is not as clean as everyone thought it was,'' he said. `` It breaks apart at different times and has debris as large as an automobile and as small as a piece of small shrapnel. The issue concerns the spread of debris and the fragmentation of the <ORGANIZATION> SRB </ORGANIZATION> when it disintegrates.''
</TEXT>
