<HEAD>Direct-Mail Falloff Causes Decline In Donations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Americans are giving less to the two major political parties, and Republicans hold a smaller fund-raising lead over Democrats than before, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> says. The <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION> said in a report released Monday that contributions to five fund-raising committees operated by each party totaled some $ 226 million during the first 18 months of the 1987-88 election cycle. That was well below the $ 267 million the 10 committees took in during the corresponding period in 1983-84 when <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was heading for a second term as president. The $ 226 million also was about $ 1 million below the combined take for the first 18 months of the 1985-86 cycle, a non-presidential election period when contributions usually are less than in presidential years. The <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION> said contributions to the five <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> committees totaled $ 166.19 million during the 18 months ending June 30, compared with $ 59.84 million raised by the five Democratic counterparts in the same period. That left the Republicans in front by $ 106.35 million, but their lead was smaller than the $ 152.7 million bulge during the corresponding period in 1985-86 and the $ 147.85 million advantage for the first three quarters of the 1983-84 election cycle. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> report covered the finances of the Democratic and Republican national committees; their <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> campaign committees; their national convention funds; and their state-local finance committees. The <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> saw its 1987-88 receipts fall to $ 61.58 million, the lowest point for a similar 18-month period during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> presidency. Corresponding figures were $ 64.16 million in 1985-86, $ 75.23 million in 1983-84 and $ 65.75 million in 1981-82. <PERSON> Kathryn </PERSON> <PERSON> Murray </PERSON>, the committee's communications director, blamed the falloff on poor response to the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION>'s direct-mail solicitations in the first and second quarters of 1987. During this period, the scandals that rocked the television evangelists hurt direct-mail appeals by the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> and a variety of non-political fund-raisers, according to <PERSON> Murray </PERSON>. She said that since then, contributions have picked up, with the second quarter of this year running second only to a three-month period in 1984. The National Republican <ORGANIZATION> Senatorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which support <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> candidates in races for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, also showed lower receipts in the first 18 months of this election cycle. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee reported contributions of $ 42.3 million, down from a 1980s high of $ 65.81 million in 1985-86. The House apparatus had receipts of $ 21.32 million, nearly half the $ 41.96 it had in the first 18 months of the 1983-84 cycle. On the Democratic side, contributions to the five entities in the current cycle were only about $ 98,000 above where they were at the same period in the last presidential cycle. The <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which relies less than its Republican counterpart on direct-mail solicitations, had receipts of $ 16.85 million, down from the $ 29.76 million taken in during 1983-84. This drop, however, was offset by increased giving to the <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committees and their committees for state and local party affairs. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> panel received $ 11.42 million, compared with a previous high of $ 7.56 million in 1985-86. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel was at $ 9.45 million, up from $ 8.74 million in 1985-86. The state-local share was $ 12.64 million, compared with a previous high of $ 10.97 million in 1983-84.
