<SECOND>PM-Burma-Chaos,0678</SECOND>
<HEAD>Analysts: Authorities May be Sowing Chaos to Retake Control</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s besieged government and military may be deliberately pushing the country toward anarchy in an attempt to reassert control after 26 years of authoritarian rule, diplomats and other analysts say. Remaining silent since Aug. 19, the government has withdrawn troops and police from the streets while looting and other crimes reportedly go unchecked. Civilian administration has ceased to function in many areas. There have been increasing reports and some witness accounts of military agents seeking to provoke tensions. The state media has reported nine almost simultaneous prison uprisings in widely different areas of the country and the escape or release of nearly 9,000 inmates. `` My impression is it is strongly possible that this chaos is being planned by state authorities to give them good reasons to intervene eventually,'' said a Japanese diplomat in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> capital. However, others, also speaking on condition of anonymity, caution that with virtually no access to the current leadership analysts can at best make educated guesses on its intentions. One Western diplomat watching developments from <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> said the drift towards chaos may simply reflect confusion within the leadership coupled with an `` arrogance, an unwillingess to accept that they have to give up.'' `` There's an obvious vacuum with students and others trying to find some leadership. The obvious people to step into the vacuum are the military, conspiratorially or not,'' an <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> diplomat in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> said. The leadership withdrew into itself following the announcement Aug. 19 _ after months of bloody anti-government rioting in which hundreds were killed _ that civilian lawyer <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> had replaced the widely hated <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> as president and head of the sole political party. <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON>'s promise of a referendum on Sept. 12 that would pave the way for democracy did not quiet the protests that have erupted throughout <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> in the past month. Unsatisfied opposition leaders demanded an interim government and the end of one-party rule. A number of Burmese and some outsider observers believed that <PERSON> Ne </PERSON> <PERSON> Win </PERSON>, who formally retired in late July after wielding almost absolute power for 26 years, was still pulling strings behind the scenes along with loyal military officers. Leaders have urged that demonstrations remain peaceful so the government can not take advantage of the turmoil. `` The public must be united and well disciplined ... people must be alert to prevent machinations of destructive elements to create anarchy in the country,'' a former defense minister, Tin Oo, told an anti-government rally last week. In <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> and other areas, `` democracy centers'' and block committees have replaced judicial and civil authorities to maintain law and order. Whether such makeshift measures will stop the growing lawlessness, widespread strikes, soaring commodity prices and food shortages remains a crucial question. One Swedish journalist and <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> expert, <PERSON> Bertil </PERSON> <PERSON> Lintner </PERSON>, notes that <PERSON> Ne </PERSON> <PERSON> Win </PERSON> and his military followers used the pretext of domestic turmoil and threats to national security to seize power from a democratic government in 1962. `` The government ca n't control the situation so they are letting things get worse. They hope the people will beg them to come back. It's vicious,'' <PERSON> Lintner </PERSON> said, quoting a <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> proverb that translates: `` If you ca n't eat the beef yourself, throw sand on it.'' One Bangkok-based diplomat said the students and other anti-government forces might react dramatically to keep up their hitherto remarkable momentum. `` The students have been the engine of change and used a lot of imagination. But now they have to take a new initiative,'' he said. `` There appears to be a paralysis in the government. A hiatus has set in and nobody knows what to do next,'' the diplomat said. Referring to Ne Win, he added: `` In every dictator there is an element of contempt for the people. He ca n't accept that the people no longer want him.''
