<HEAD>Canine Virus Believed To Be Seal Killer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PIETERBUREN, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A virus common in dogs has killed more than 11,000 seals in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s coastal waters this summer and humans can do little to stop the spread of the disease, a Dutch biologist says. Up to 80 percent of the seals in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kattegat </LOCATION> waters between <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> might die, <PERSON> Ab </PERSON> <PERSON> Osterhaus </PERSON> told a news conference Monday. `` Canine distemper virus, or a closely related virus, is the primary cause of the seal deaths,'' said <PERSON> Osterhaus </PERSON> in this northern Dutch village, which has <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s largest seal nursery. The virus causes infections of the respiratory and central nervous systems and the digestive tracts. <PERSON> Osterhaus </PERSON> said no specific cure exists for seals with the virus. Distemper may have spread to seals when one was bitten by a dog, said <PERSON> Osterhaus </PERSON>, who works for the <ORGANIZATION> Dutch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION>. Specialists in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> who have been investigating the seal deaths have speculated that pollution has played a role in the killer epidemic. <PERSON> Osterhaus </PERSON> said research is still being conducted to determine if the massive pollution of Western European waters could have accelerated the epidemic by weakening seals' immune systems. `` We know that certain substances we find in the seas today ... can affect the immune system,'' he said. `` Pollution may have triggered the thing but it was not the cause as such.'' <PERSON> Osterhaus </PERSON> said antibodies to canine distemper virus were found in all of the dead seals he examined: `` The development of these antibodies coincided clearly with the surfacing of symptoms'' of the disease. A similar report was made at a news conference Monday in <LOCATION> Stockholm </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, by patholigist <PERSON> Anders </PERSON> <PERSON> Bergman </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Stockholm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s veterinary school. He said he began suspecting in June that the canine distemper virus was linked to the seal deaths. <PERSON> Bengt </PERSON> <PERSON> Klingeborn </PERSON>, a virologist at the veterinary school, said he believed the 25 percent of Western European seals that have survived so far will live through the epidemic because they have developed antibodies. <PERSON> Osterhaus </PERSON> noted that there had been an outbreak of the canine distemper virus among dogs in <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION> shortly before the epidemic broke out among seals early this year. Each summer, thousands of seals migrate from <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION> to Western European waters. <PERSON> Osterhaus </PERSON> said his team had developed an experimental vaccine against the canine distemper virus but added `` it will not be possible to carry out preventive vaccinations in the wild.'' <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> has reported 3,400 dead seals, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> nearly 3,000, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> 3,900, <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> 600 and the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> 175.
</TEXT>
