<HEAD>Abbie Hoffman Makes NYC Comedy Debut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Have you heard the one about the wisecracking political prankster who switched to stand-up comedy? No one could tell the difference. Erstwhile <PERSON> Yippie </PERSON> <PERSON> Abbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>, fresh from a reunion of demonstrators from the 1968 Democratic convention in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, made his <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> comedy debut Monday night at an Upper West Side club. <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>, whose humor and courtroom antics got national attention during the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> 7 trial, spent more than an hour needling `` Actor in Chief'' <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and the Republicans, and reminiscing. Predictably, vice-presidential candidate <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> came in for a few jabs: `` looks like a hawk, runs like a chicken.'' <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>, 51, wore a blue sweater with white stars and red stripes _ reminding the audience of his arrest for wearing similar garb in the'60s _ then stripped to a `` Just Say No'' T-shirt. In addition to politics and protest, <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>'s topics of choice were drugs, sex and religion. Straightforward jokes were rare, and rambling stories and observations the norm. As one of the 150 or so who paid $ 13.50 for the show at Stand Up NY said, `` <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Leno </PERSON> does n't have to worry.'' <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> had performed his comedy act in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> before coming to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. During a question-and-answer session, he was asked why he took up comedy. He replied that his talks on college campuses always got laughs and `` it was n't hard to pull out all the elements of humor from the talk.'' <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>, who lives in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, spoke of his three children _ `` not a yuppie in the litter'' _ and p