 Pulitzer Prize-winning playwright <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Shepard </PERSON> says he learned to direct his first feature film the way he learned everything else: just doing it. `` You can study things until they're over the hill _ read a lot of books, see a lot of films,'' <PERSON> Shepard </PERSON> says in the September issue of <LOCATION> Vogue </LOCATION>. `` But the only way to learn something is simply to do it. Just step across the fence.'' <PERSON> Shepard </PERSON> has acted in several films but `` Far North,'' due out next month, is his first directorial effort. It stars <PERSON> Jessica </PERSON> <PERSON> Lange </PERSON>, his live-in lover, and was shot entirely in northern <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, where she was born and grew up. <PERSON> Shepard </PERSON>, whose plays include the 1979 Pulitzer Prize-winning `` Buried Child,'' `` True West,'' `` Fool for Love'' and `` A Lie of the Mind,'' says he does n't get very excited about acting. `` But filmmaking I can get passionate about because it's a natural extension of writing,'' he said. `` It's everything you wish writing could be: you can visualize things, and there they are; you can extend shots, change the colors, put wind in when the wind is n't there.''
