<BYLINE>By VICENTE LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The 10-year-old daughter of a couple presumed killed by security forces during <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s `` dirty war'' was ordered taken from her natural grandparents and returned to her adoptive parents Federal Judge <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanudo </PERSON>, who handed down the decision, `` does n't deserve to live,'' said <PERSON> Ruben </PERSON> <PERSON> Fontana </PERSON>, <PERSON> Juliana </PERSON>'s maternal grandfather. <PERSON> Fontana </PERSON> vowed to appeal the order, issued Monday in a closed-door hearing in the <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION> suburb of Moron. <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> and <PERSON> Carmen </PERSON> <PERSON> Trevino </PERSON> adopted the dark, chubby-cheeked <PERSON> Juliana </PERSON> after she was found as an infant in the doorway of a building and taken to an orphanage. They did not comment on the ruling to reporters outside the courtroom. The `` Juliana Case,'' as it is called in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, is reminiscent of `` The Official Story,'' the Oscar-winning 1985 Argentine film about a family that adopts the child of a woman killed by security forces. In the 1970s, at least 9,000 people vanished in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and were presumed abducted and killed by security agents in the `` dirty war,'' which was ordered by the military dictatorship to quell the leftist opposition. Several military leaders have been tried, convicted and sentenced for their role in the terror. The <ORGANIZATION> Trevinos </ORGANIZATION> _ unlike other families who did n't question where their children came from _ adopted <PERSON> Juliana </PERSON> legally, told her she was adopted, and tried for years to track down her biological parents. <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Trevino </PERSON>, a journalist, recently told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>: `` From the first moment, we told <PERSON> Juliana </PERSON> she was adopted ... If her real parents appeared, my wife and I told ourselves we would rip up the documents'' and return the child. The <ORGANIZATION> Trevinos </ORGANIZATION> brought <PERSON> Juliana </PERSON> to the attention of her natural grandparents earlier this year, when they gave a sample of her blood to a clinic set up to match children with parents who had `` disappeared.'' The blood sample proved <PERSON> Juliana </PERSON> was the daughter of <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Fabian </PERSON> <PERSON> Sandoval </PERSON> and <PERSON> Liliana </PERSON> <PERSON> Fontana </PERSON> _ who was pregnant when the couple was arrested on July 1, 1977 _ and the granddaughter of <PERSON> Ruben </PERSON> and <PERSON> Clelia </PERSON> <PERSON> Fontana </PERSON>. On June 23, the day the <ORGANIZATION> Trevinos </ORGANIZATION> received the news from the blood bank, they were ordered to appear in court. Former Federal Judge <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON> <PERSON> Padilla </PERSON> gave them two choices: return <PERSON> Juliana </PERSON> to her grandparents, or give her to a foster home. The <ORGANIZATION> Trevinos </ORGANIZATION> chose the former, but filed an appeal arguing that they had followed the legal requirements to adopt <PERSON> Juliana </PERSON> and were better suited to care for her than the grandparents. <PERSON> Sanudo </PERSON>, who replaced <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON> <PERSON> Padilla </PERSON> after the latter retired, overturned his predecessor's ruling. The military, which staged a 1976 coup, turned over power to elected civilian President <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> in 1983.
