<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Twenty-nine people arrested while trying to give food to homeless people in <LOCATION> Golden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gate </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> chanted `` arrest hunger, not free food'' as police led them away. Police cited the activists for illegal distribution of food, demonstrating and leafleting without a permit and creating a public nuisance. `` By sending the police here, the mayor's saying it's illegal to feed people,'' said <PERSON> Stephanie </PERSON> <PERSON> Hedgecoke </PERSON>, an organizer for a group called `` All Peoples <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>.'' The arrests were made Monday after about 100 members of the group called `` Food Not Bombs'' marched through the <LOCATION> Haight-Ashbury </LOCATION> district to the park, carrying boxes of food, chanting slogans and banging pots and pans. When they reached the corner of the park just before noon, the members began to set up two tables with plates of beans, melons and other food. About 50 police officers, half clad in riot gear, surrounded the group and arrested members after issuing a warning. `` We do n't want to have a confrontation,'' said <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> McHenry </PERSON>, spokesman for Food Not Bombs. `` We have been doing this for eight years in other cities.'' <PERSON> McHenry </PERSON>, who was also arrested, said his group supported diverting funds for military arms to humanitarian causes. `` Our political message is that money should be spent on food and housing,'' he said. The city had warned group members they would be arrested if they attempted to give away food in the park, something they had done for several months. The group said the police crackdown was the result of complaints from local businesses. One resident who watched the arrests said she was disgusted by the police action. `` As a citizen of the city, I was offended that this was going on in my neighborhood,'' said <PERSON> Marjorie </PERSON> <PERSON> Antenore </PERSON>, a teache