<HEAD>With PM-Wildfires-Commander, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As forest fires spread through the West, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> is spreading the word: Help! The <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> has put out a call for temporary firefighters to battle the hundreds of blazes scorching the West's timberlands. But the emergency help must endure backbreaking labor, smoke and flame. And only local people need apply. Meanwhile, governors in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> called up National Guardsmen today to help fight fires in their states. The <ORGANIZATION> Boise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interagency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> has notified <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> regions affected by the dozens of out of control fires that temporary firefighters may be hired on a contingency basis, said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferris </PERSON>, information officer for the center that coordinates fire suppression in the West. The temporary `` emergency firefighting hires,'' or `` casuals,'' must have the physical and mental capacity to work on the fire lines, including long days of shoveling and chopping on steep hillsides very near burning timber, <PERSON> Ferris </PERSON> said. `` The job carries with it a lot of drama and romance,'' <PERSON> Ferris </PERSON> said. `` But somedays you've got to ask yourself, ` Why am I doing this?''' `` What we're doing is only hiring from the local community,'' he said. `` I've had people calling from all over the country, and some wanting to volunteer. I've had people wanting to take their vacation and work, if you can believe that.'' <PERSON> Ferris </PERSON> said those interested should contact their local national forest office, not the <LOCATION> Boise </LOCATION> center and not the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C </LOCATION>. Applicants will undergo an aerobic stress test, which measures the ability of the heart to recover from exertion. While some fire officials have set the total number of temporary workers needed at 4,000, <PERSON> Ferris </PERSON> said each national forest must determine its requirements and the cost of employing those extra people. `` We're making assessments about our needs in the situation. We're not saying we're going to hire 4,000 or 8,000,'' he said. The emergency labor is a unique situation in a unique fire year. Late last week, the fire center estimated that 66,000 fires had scorched more than 3.3 million acres, mostly in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. There are 547 20-member crews, or 10,940 regular firefighters, battling the West's fires, <PERSON> Ferris </PERSON> said. Nearly 1,600 water pumper trucks are manned by 15,213 people, or an average three crew members per vehicle. About 630 people are flying in helicopters for aerial observation or water drops. And 2,400 soldiers have been called to the lines, <PERSON> Ferris </PERSON> said. That does not include the scores of people who have contracted to cut timber, cater meals at fire camps or bulldoze lines. The <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> does not expect to have the `` casuals'' trained and fitted for fighting fires until Friday, <PERSON> Ferris </PERSON> said. `` We will not put them in a situation that is more than what they can bite and chew,'' he said.
