<HEAD>Federal Judge Sentences Drug Smuggler to Life in Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge ordered a convicted drug smuggler `` removed from society'' and sentenced him to life in prison without parole for his role in importing 150 tons of Colombian marijuana. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Castoro </PERSON>, 39, `` introduced more harm and evil into this society than a murderer,'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Fawsett </PERSON> said Monday in imposing the harshest penalty ever handed down in federal court in <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION>. The judge also gave <PERSON> Castoro </PERSON> an additional 65 years in prison on drug and tax convictions and fined him $ 200,000. <PERSON> Castoro </PERSON> was convicted in July on a charge of conducting a continuing criminal enterprise and nine other drug possession and tax-evasion counts. Federal drug agents and other witnesses testified he was one of two major figures controlling a ring that unloaded drug-laden freighters in the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION> and smuggled the marijuana on speedboats into <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> from 1977 to 1984.
