<BYLINE>By GARRY MITCHELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANDALUSIA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A mayor accused of `` voodoo'' antics undermined the legal process by granting pardons to repeat offenders and pocketed payments of some fines, the city attorney testified at his impeachment trial. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Grissett </PERSON>, the city attorney, testified Monday at the trial of <LOCATION> Florala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mayor </LOCATION> <LOCATION> H.T </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mathis </PERSON> that he had warned the 85-year-old official about abusing his legal authority to grant pardons. Charges against <PERSON> Mathis </PERSON>, who is accused of incompetence and damaging his small town's reputation with `` voodoo'' antics, include wholesale pardoning of convicted drunken drivers. `` It's my turn -LRB- today -RRB-,'' the mayor said Monday at the conclusion of the first day of his trial in <ORGANIZATION> Covington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. Early today, three of the mayor's supporters stood outside the courthouse carrying placards that said `` Impeach <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Siegelman </PERSON>,'' the state attorney general who rarely appears at trials but joined his aides at this one. <PERSON> Grissett </PERSON> also testified that the town of 5,000, located near the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> border, was forced to file suit against the mayor to prevent him from accepting payments of some fines and depositing them in his personal account. `` He was taking partial payments outside court on the installment basis,'' <PERSON> Grissett </PERSON> told the jury. He said <PERSON> Mathis </PERSON> deposited $ 225 in fines in his personal account and did not return the money `` until I filed suit.'' <PERSON> Mathis </PERSON>' attorney, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Prestwood </PERSON>, questioned <PERSON> Grissett </PERSON> about the mayor's authority to grant pardons. The attorney conceded that <PERSON> Mathis </PERSON> had that power, but contended that he had abused it by granting pardons to repeat offenders. <PERSON> Siegelman </PERSON> and a county grand jury accused <PERSON> Mathis </PERSON> of misusing his office by granting too many pardons for drunken drivers. The mayor is accused of willful neglect of duty, incompetency in office and corruption. <PERSON> Mathis </PERSON>, whose four-year term expires Oct. 3, attracted national attention by sprinkling so-called `` voodoo dust'' around City Hall and later proclaiming `` National Voodoo Week'' in <LOCATION> Florala </LOCATION>. He says he sprinkled the powder as a joke. In opening arguments, <PERSON> Prestwood </PERSON> portrayed <PERSON> Mathis </PERSON> as the victim of a political struggle with the City Council. But Councilman <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> testified that the `` voodoo'' dusting incident had damaged the town's reputation and that the mayor offered no explanation except to say, `` When it works, he would let us know.'' <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said the council had to obtain a court order to halt the mayor from releasing people from jail. `` He would order the dispatcher to turn people out of jail,'' <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said. Later, the mayor began granting pardons to those in custody. In other testimony, several <LOCATION> Florala </LOCATION> residents who had been arrested on minor offenses said they had pawned their cars to the mayor in exchange for payment of fines. They said they later reimbursed <PERSON> Mathis </PERSON> in amounts larger than the fines to get their cars back. In one instance, however, <PERSON> Rachael </PERSON> <PERSON> Aplin </PERSON> said the mayor had already sold her car to the daughter of a city councilman and she was unable to get the vehicle back. <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> officials found guilty of impeachment charges are only removed from office, not fined or sent to jail. However, they can face another trial for the same crimes. An official thrown out of office can appeal the verdict directly to the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>.
