<HEAD>South Africa Completes Troop Withdrawal From Angola</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede JOHANNESBURG</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs on withdrawal. Picks up 5th graf pvs ``An
estimated...''. Changes byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> RUNDU </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ The last <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> troops withdrew today from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> after fighting for more than a year in support of anti-Marxist guerrillas. The armed forces chief of staff, Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> Gleeson </PERSON>, said at a ceremony that nearly 1,000 soldiers crossed into <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> during the day as part of a regional peace accord. `` As of this moment, we are out of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Gleeson </PERSON> said. South African and foreign journalists were flown to <LOCATION> Rundu </LOCATION>, on the Angolan border, to witness what the final stages of the withdrawal of South African forces. They saw 50 military vehicles cross a pontoon bridge over the <LOCATION> Okavango </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> before the bridge was dismantled. In <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, also known as <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, military officials said security forces in the past week killed 14 guerrillas fighting to end South African rule over the territory. South African forces also staged their first amphibious landing exercise today on the Namibian coast. South African forces have been in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> since early 1987. The pullout from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> is part of a cease-fire agreement that is intended to clear the way for withdrawal of about 50,000 Cuban troops from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and independence for <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. An estimated 2,500 South African troops in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> have been leaving since a cease-fire was declared Aug. 8. The Cuban troops support <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s Marxist government in its 13-year-old war against guerrillas of <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> for the Total Independence of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> -RRB-. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> back <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> is not party to the cease-fire and was excluded from recent peace talks held by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> mediation. There have been unconfirmed reports that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has been reinforcing its line of bases in northern <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. The amphibious landing exercise was conducted on a beach near <LOCATION> Walvis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, a South African enclave that serves as <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>'s only commercial port. High-speed landing craft carried marines and paratroopers ashore as part of a six-week exercise involving about 2,500 military personnel. The <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, the main pro-independence movement in the territory, contends <LOCATION> Walvis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> should become part of a sovereign <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s deputy defense minister, <PERSON> Wynand </PERSON> <PERSON> Breytenbach </PERSON>, said Monday the port would remain under South African control and continue to serve as a military base. The South African-led territorial army said today that 14 <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas have been killed in the last week. <LOCATION> SWAPO </LOCATION>, considered likely to take power if independence elections are held, has said it will observe a cease-fire in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> starting Thursday if <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> reciprocates. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> says it will begin withdrawing from <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> on Nov. 1 and allow the territory to hold independence elections next June 1 if Cuban troops leave <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> by the latter date. The four countries involved in the negotiations met last week in <LOCATION> Brazzaville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Congo </LOCATION>, but failed to agree on a timetable for <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> withdrawal from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and Namibian independence. More talks are planned next week. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has intervened in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> regularly since 1975 when it invaded the country on the eve of Angolan independence from <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> advanced several hundred miles up <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s west coast before turning back South African forces returned to <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> several times in the early 1980s, but in May 1985 announced a complete withdrawal. Several weeks later, two South African commandos were killed and a third was captured in northernmost <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. Thousands of South African troops entered <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> in 1987 to assist <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION>. South African generals said their maximum strength in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> was 3,000 men, although other reports claimed the force was twice that size during heavy fighting last October. In November, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> said its forces again had begun withdrawing, but most of the troops remained until this month. Dozens of white South African troops, most of them conscripts, have been killed in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> the past year. Black units, including Angolans fighting for <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, are believed to have suffered heavier casualties, but no comprehensive figures have been released.
