<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The four-man junta met today to nominate the sole candidate _ expected to be President <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> _ in a presidential referendum that could extend <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s rule until 1997. National police troops cordoned off the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> building where army commander Gen. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> navy </ORGANIZATION> chief Adm. <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Merino </PERSON>, air force commander Gen. <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Matthei </PERSON> and national police director Gen. <PERSON> Rodolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Stange </PERSON> began their nomination session at noon behind closed doors. Their selection will be presented for ratification or rejection in an October referendum. Under the election rules established by the military government, <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> _ who deposed the elected president in a bloody 1973 military coup _ and the other three junta members were to name a single nominee and voters will vote `` yes'' or `` no'' on that candidate. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, Merino, <PERSON> Matthei </PERSON> and <PERSON> Stange </PERSON>, all in dress military uniforms, arrived one at a time at the ministry building, entering on a thick red carpet rolled out for the occasion. None made any remarks. While the other commanders arrived by car, the 72-year-old <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> and his entourage of aides and bodyguards came on foot from the government palace directly across <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>'s central boulevard. He was both cheered and booed by bystanders. Both pro-and anti-Pinochet groups planned demonstrations in connection with the nomination. Gen. <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Torres </PERSON>, national police sub-director, said `` we have certainly taken some special security measures, especially in the slums, where some day there might be problems. `` We do n't expect serious problems,'' he added. <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> Undersecretary <PERSON> Alberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardemil </PERSON> told reporters `` there is total and complete calm throughout the country. And I do n't think the government will need to take any extraordinary measures. On Monday, police used water cannons to scatter a downtown demonstration by women chanting anti-government slogans and urging voters to vote `` no'' in the referendum. Witnesses said about 25 people were arrested. If a majority of <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s 7.2 million registered voters cast `` yes'' ballots in the referendum, the nominee will begin an eight-year term March 11. If a majority reject him, an open election will be held in 1990, with <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> remaining in power until then. The 1980 Constitution gives the junta 48 hours to nominate a candidate. Were the commanders to fail to reach a unanimous decision within that time, the Constitution calls for nomination by majority decision of an eight-man <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, which includes <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, navy chief Adm. <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Merino </PERSON>, air force commander Gen. <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Matthei </PERSON> and national police director Gen. <PERSON> Rodolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Stange </PERSON>. It also includes four other officials, three of whom are appointed by <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>. Opposition leaders said they had little doubt that <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> would win a quick nomination and called on followers to bang empty pots and pans inside their homes tonight in protest. `` It will be the noisiest pot-banging ever heard,'' predicted <PERSON> Ricardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lagos </PERSON>, a socialist and co-leader of a 16-party opposition coalition. Members of the youth wings of several opposition parties and a communist-controlled slum dwellers organization planned street demonstrations in central <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>. The defense minister, Adm. <PERSON> Patricio </PERSON> <PERSON> Carvajal </PERSON>, warned Monday that `` the government will not allow any violent demonstrations. They will be suppressed by police.'' <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> led the coup that ousted the elected government of Marxist President <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Allende </PERSON> in September 1973.
