<TEXT>
 A federal judge today rejected a request to unseal search warrants and other court documents used in the search of the homes of three men in connection with the government's probe of defense contractors. The decision by <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> Chief Judge <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> was a setback for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> which had persuaded a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> magistrate to unseal some of the documents in July. In overturning the magistrate's ruling, <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> agreed with the government that making the papers public could impede the government's probe. <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> also said the three <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> men, whose homes were searched under the warrants, had not been criminally charged. Since they were merely under investigation, <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> said they had a right to privacy.
