<HEAD>Bentsen Gleeful Over `Lesser' Opponent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sometimes, Democratic vice presidential candidate <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> seems barely able to control his glee over his Republican rival, fellow Sen. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>. When <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> first picked the <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> senator, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> hailed it as `` good news.'' With <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> soon swamped in controversy, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> was asked what he would do if he were <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` Sweat,'' he said. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, 67, is one of the lions of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> after 18 years. He's chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, sponsor of some of the most important legislation of the decade, a successful businessman and decorated World War II bomber pilot. By comparison, in experience and accomplishments, the 41-year-old <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> pales _ `` not a member of the club,'' sniffed one top <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Democratic aide. And occasionally, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> lets slip that he really does n't think <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> measures up. In eight years in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> has been known mostly for his fight for President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s Strategic Defense Initiative, his battle for the controversial federal court appointment of <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Manion </PERSON> and a losing fight against the 60-day notification for plant closings. `` I do n't remember anything in particular,'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said, when asked if he had squared off against <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> on any other issues. And he makes repeated subtle references to <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s youth. `` I certainly do n't think he's too young but certainly you've got to have some maturity'' to be a heartbeat away from the presidency, he said at one <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> stop When reporters goaded <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> with questions on whether <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> would still be on the ticket Nov. 8, the Texan finally could n't resist. `` I hope so,'' he said. But away from the public eye, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> and his top aides are concerned about going into debate against <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> is younger than President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was when he won the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, but his face looks older, especially on television. The campaign has signed him up for coaching and makeup consultation so he wo n't appear wooden when put side-by-side with the handsome <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>. And while a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> record takes years of consistent work, a televised debate is measured in 30-second bites. A well-briefed <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, given the right format, could hold his own. And holding his own might be good enough to be declared the winner, given the low expectations accorded the <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> senator. `` We're on the wrong end of the expectations game, as far as the vice presidential debate is concerned, because everyone expects Sen. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> to do so well,'' said <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Peek </PERSON>, a long-time <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Democratic strategist who is now a private consultant in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Other Democrats already are defending <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, in advance of a debate that may never come off. `` The senator is concerned about a debate because his style as a senator is to get things done and he does n't engage in a lot of sparring on the floor,'' national party spokesman <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> McCurry </PERSON> said. On the other hand, `` It's easy to envision <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> as a TV talk show host.'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> also must be careful not to bludgeon <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> and win him a backlash of sympathy among voters, as has occurred in the recent controversy over <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> record. <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Ornstein </PERSON>, who studies politics at the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, says the Democrats have reason to worry about <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>. `` He is not a dummy,'' <PERSON> Ornstein </PERSON> said. In past debates, such as when he defeated incumbent <PERSON> Birch </PERSON> <PERSON> Bayh </PERSON> to win the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in 1980, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> showed `` when he was prepared, well-briefed, and focused, he could do all right.'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, meanwhile, has the difficult task of not wanting to help the Republicans in their expectations game and also not wanting to speak well of <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>. `` It is n't in <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>'s interest to talk about <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Ornstein </PERSON> said. So while he clearly sees <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> as a lesser opponent, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> must focus his attacks away from the man and back to the issues and <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s conservative voting record. `` I do n't want to get into his personal life. That I do n't want to do,'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> says. Then <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> hints about which Republican would have been a worthy opponent. `` I thought it would be <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, frankly,'' he says. `` It's a real gamble picking <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, and I think it's going to be proven that way.''
