<SECOND>AM-Katyn Massacre,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plaque to be Dedicated to Slain Polish Officers at Katyn</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A delegation from <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> will take part in a ceremony this week honoring the 4,000 Polish officers slain in the <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Forest </LOCATION>, although the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is not taking responsiblity for the World War II massacre, a government spokesman said. A joint Soviet-Polish investigation into the killings has not been completed and the `` final truth'' about responsibility is still to be determined, said <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON>. For years, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> government has blamed the killings in the forest near <LOCATION> Smolensk </LOCATION>, 250 miles west of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, on <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> occupation forces. The Kremlin has maintained the massacre occurred in the fall of 1941, after the invasion of Nazi forces in June of that year. But Western historians contend the Soviet state security and police force carried out the massacre in April 1940. The Polish officers had been taken prisoner by Soviet soldiers in 1939 during the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s campaign against <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. Since <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> came to power in 1985, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> have labeled the <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> massacre a `` blank spot'' _ a taboo or disputed issue _ in the two nations' histories. They have set up a joint commission of historians to investigate the killings. One Soviet historian, <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Latshev </PERSON>, has been quoted as saying he saw evidence that Soviet bullets were found in bodies exhumed at <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION>. Many Poles were disappointed that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> did not mention the <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> massacre during a visit to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> in July. <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> told reporters at a regular news briefing an official <LOCATION> Polish </LOCATION> delegation will witness the unveiling of a plaque at a `` memorial complex''' during a ceremony at <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> on Thursday. `` A commemorative plaque will be set up there with the following inscription: ` A memorial complex to Polish officers who perished at <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> and a monument to Soviet prisoners-of-war will be erected in this place,''' <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> said. The Polish visitors plan to lay wreaths on the site, he said. The dedication of the plaque did not mean the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> was accepting responsiblity for the massacre but that `` anyway, the time has come for a monument to be built there,'' <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> said. On May 28, <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> reported Soviet officials participated in a ceremony the day before at <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> at a recently renovated monument to `` the Polish officers shot dead by the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> in 1941.'' The report went on to say that version of the massacre was being reconsidered. It was not clear whether the monument was part of the same complex to which <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> referred. He said in a telephone interview after the briefing he was unaware of the May ceremony at <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> and believed the memorial complex was still under construction at that time. He said he did not know why the inscription on the monument, which specifically blames the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> and gives a date for the massacre, differs from the one on the new plaque, which places no blame or date.
