<HEAD>Sandinista Troops On Alert During Fragile Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO BLANCO, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sandinista troops are patrolling in rural areas, undergoing intensive training and staying on the alert during a fragile cease-fire with Contra rebels. The government's combat units have spent time regrouping, and farmers in this combat area about 80 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> said they have been able to plant crops despite lingering tension. Each side has charged the other with violating the cease-fire during the five months it has been in effect, but the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> recognize their advantage. `` The Contras do n't have much of a possibility of major attacks,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman Maj. <PERSON> Rosa </PERSON> <PERSON> Pasos </PERSON> in a recent interview in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. Most of the Contras trying to overthrow the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> have holed up in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> and they are continuing to train new fighters and ask for weapons from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Each side says the other is planning for renewed combat, and <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> Cardinal <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> y <PERSON> Bravo </PERSON> recently charged both sides with preparing to renew the almost seven-year war. The 9-year-old Sandinista government and Contra leaders signed a cease-fire agreement March 23, three weeks after the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> cut off military aid to the rebels. Talks to define the pact, which called for democratic reforms and an end to rebel attacks, broke off June 9. Contra officials and <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> estimate that some 2,000 rebels remain inside <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, mostly in the rugged northern mountains. Peasants in eastern <LOCATION> Matagalpa </LOCATION>, a northern province that has seen heavy combat during the war, said <PERSON> Contra </PERSON> rebels ambushed several civilian cars and military vehicles recently on the remote dirt roads. Many motorists venturing along the rutted 20-mile stretch from <LOCATION> Matiguas </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Blanco </LOCATION>, a longtime <LOCATION> Contra </LOCATION> route, fly white flags to mark their neutrality while journeying through the area. `` This road runs along the Contra corridor to the north to <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>,'' a Sandinista military officer, <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, said at the <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Blanco </LOCATION> base overlooking steep hills. `` Here you ca n't say any road is safe.'' <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said the rebels, most in torn uniforms or civilian clothes, kidnapped more than a dozen civilians recently. In the town of <LOCATION> Matiguas </LOCATION>, several residents said the combat in the region was sharply reduced but that an air of tension remained. `` It's quiet by comparison,'' said farmer <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sequira </PERSON>. `` But we just wait and see.'' The farmer and government officials said the lull in the war meant many peasants planted crops this spring for the first time in several years. `` But we do n't know if we'll be able to reap the harvest,'' said <PERSON> Sequira </PERSON>. A series of informal talks started by Sandinista troops with <ORGANIZATION> Contra </ORGANIZATION> combatants ended in May. An army officer said the rebels responded to messages with bullets. Contra leader <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON> said recently the chats were `` part of a Sandinista trick to dismantle us one by one.'' Contra officials report that most of their forces fled during the past four months to tent camps in eastern <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, where more than 9,000 combatants are receiving U.S.-supplied food and uniforms. Rebel commanders said recently they are prepared to return to the battlefields in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> but needed weapons, denied by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> since Feb. 29. Many are now armed with rusted Soviet-designed Kalashnikov rifles. The Sandinistas, supplied by the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, last year received $ 505 million in war supplies, according to the Pentagon. The Nicaraguan <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman said shipments were arriving this year `` as usual,'' but declined to elaborate. Army troops, <PERSON> Pasos </PERSON> said in an interview, were moving into areas where Contra presence had been strong and were seeking civilian support by backing health and educational services. At rebel base camps in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, Contra officials said the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> are getting ready for an attack aimed at finishing the Contras once and for all. The Sandinista troops, <PERSON> Pasos </PERSON> said, were refining combat skills, looking at new tactics to counter Contra ambushes and staying in the field. `` Our combat troops are in position,'' Pasos said. Asked about any plans to reduce <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s 80,000-strong armed forces, the largest in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, she replied: `` For what? The war has n't ended.'' More than 26,000 people have been killed since the fighting started in 1981, a 18 months after the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> overthrew dictator <PERSON> Anastasio </PERSON> <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON>.
