he practice of making decisions in private about nomination of people to the highest positions, and a person was judged by his family status and the ability to please this or that clan, and not by his business qualities,'' the newspaper said. The <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency has reported that <PERSON> Churbanov </PERSON> is accused of accepting bribes totaling more than $ 1.1 million, equivalent to 270 years' pay for the average Soviet factory worker. <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> said <PERSON> Churbanov </PERSON> could face execution by firing squad because he is charged with serious economic crimes. He noted that a new version of the criminal code being drafted would reduce the use of capital punishment for economic crimes, but that this change had not yet taken effect. Selected foreign reporters will be allowed to attend the first and final days of the trial, he said.
