<HEAD>Polisario, Morocco Agree on U.N.-sponsored Peace Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Marxist-led guerrillas and <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> agreed conditionally Tuesday to a plan for a U.N.-supervised cease-fire and a referendum on the future of the disputed <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> said both sides accepted the plan for ending the 13-year conflict over the phosphate-rich <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> `` with remarks and comments.'' He declined to elaborate. The Polisario guerrillas have fought for <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION>'s independence since 1975, when <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s colonial forces gave up the northwest African territory and <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> annexed it <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> has backed Polisario's campaign, but <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> restored diplomatic relations in May after years of tension verging on war. In <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> Foreign Minister <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> <PERSON> Ordonez </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Spanish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Spain </ORGANIZATION> that he viewed the announcement as `` very good news.'' `` We expect this process to lead to the establishment of peace and prosperity in this region of great importance to <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>,'' the minister said. <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> said Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> expects to begin a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeeping operation in the region before the end of the year. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> is considering sending about 2,000 peacekeeping troops to the remote, sparsely populated territory, authorities say. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> will also be appointing a special representative to supervise the peace process, <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> said. The Aug. 11 peace plan includes the cease-fire and a referendum on the desert territory's independence or affiliation with another country, which would probably be <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>. Details of the proposal have not been made public. Determining who is eligible to vote in the referendum is considered the chief sticking point. Moroccan Foreign Minister <PERSON> Abdellatif </PERSON> <PERSON> Filali </PERSON> said a referendum could be held `` in the relatively near future ... under good conditions'' but cautioned that his side is waiting for <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> proposals on details of staging the vote. <PERSON> Bechir </PERSON> <PERSON> Mustapha </PERSON>, Polisario's No. 2 man, said his side `` accepted the formulation of the question that will be put to voters'' in a referendum. Polisario agrees to consider a 1974 census, taken when the region was under Spanish control, `` as basis'' for counting Western Saharans, <PERSON> Mustapha </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Mustapha </PERSON> said Polisario's main remaining concern is `` the future of the Moroccan administration and army,'' and that details of their retreat would have to be settled through negotiations. `` We have accepted with certain conditions,'' he said. The Organization of African Unity will have to play a major role in helping monitor a future accord along with the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Mustapha </PERSON> added. <PERSON> Filali </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mustapha </PERSON> gave <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> their replies to his peace plan offering in separate meetings at <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> office. The two sides were given a deadline of Thursday to submit responses after meeting <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> on Saturday for final clarifications on his plan. The <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> covers about 110,000 square miles but had only about 76,000 inhabitants in the last Spanish census in 1975. Most residents have fled to Moroccan-held cities or to refugee camps around the Algerian oasis of <LOCATION> Tindouf </LOCATION>. Polisario claims about 165,000 Western Saharans live around <LOCATION> Tindouf </LOCATION>, but <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> says most of them are not Western Saharans. Polisario also claims that two-thirds of the 150,000 inhabitants of the Moroccan-held areas are immigrants not eligible to vote, but <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> asserts 90 percent are Western Saharans. <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>'s army has kept Polisario from major gains, mainly by building a series of defensive walls in the desert. But <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>'s war effort has been costing up to $ 2 million a day in recent years.
