<HEAD>Comment Abroad on Quayle, Bush and Dukakis</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 This is one of a series of periodic reports compiled by <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> bureaus on how the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> presidential election campaign is viewed abroad.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Here is some of the editorial commentary appearing recently in newspapers overseas on Sen. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> vice presidential nominee, and the two main contenders in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> presidential race, Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ON QUAYLE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 _ <ORGANIZATION> Toronto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION> and Mail, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> -LRB- independent -RRB-: `` None of Mr. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s sins is mortal, but their cumulative effect is considerable As the sharks go to work, the shreds of evidence indicate that Mr. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> is a man of modest talents who has failed to impress teachers and colleagues. `` Mr. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and the Republicans face more heavy weather about Mr. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s fitness to stand a heartbeat away from the most important job in the world. They deserve it.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 _ The Independent, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> -LRB- independent -RRB-: `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s and the world's first question about <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s running mate _ Dan who _ has been comprehensively answered. ... The ... more important question _ can we image, or could we trust, a President <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>? _ will not vanish so easily. Three of the last nine presidents were replaced by their deputies before the end of their term. ... `` The furore about the <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> senator's decision to join the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> rather than go to <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> in 1969 is beginning to subside. ... It is not, however, the 22-year-old but the 41-year-old <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> whom the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people are being asked to elect. Far more disturbing than his response to a messy moral choice two decades ago is his reaction ... to personal crisis and the pitiless logic of politics in the big league. The most serious charges against Mr. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> _ callowness and shallowness _ were suggested by his first arm-flapping, finger-jabbing appearances alongside <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, before the <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> issue fully emerged. They have been confirmed by his evasive and disjointed responses to the <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> question, essentially seeking to make the issue one which it is not: the honor of the National Guard. The qualities the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and the world, has most reason to wish for in the American president are courage and coolness under fire. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> has shown little of either so far.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ON BUSH VS. DUKAKIS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 _ Las <ORGANIZATION> Ultimas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Noticias </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> -LRB- conservative -RRB-: `` <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has ahead of him the task of convincing voters that he is a capable leader It's an uphill job. ... `` <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> must also fight to keep the support _ and the contributions _ of the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s most conservative groups which do not fully trust him because they see him as a representative <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> East coast liberal wing. `` His strategy is to show <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> as a representative of the Democrats' most liberal wing whose policies include to increase spending and taxes. `` <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> trusts that, in the end, voters will seek the security of keeping in power a party and a man promising them to maintain economic growth, a curbed inflation and unchanged taxes. That is why in his speech accepting the nomination he said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> represents ` the liberal ideology that has failed'.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 _ <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Figaro </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> -LRB- conservative -RRB-: `` <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s adversary is <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> But his real problem is <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. After eight years and two terms, the president is still loved by the crowds; the vice president has only the esteem of the experts. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> electrifies the man in the street with his patriotic speeches, makes him laugh with gaffes which are generally forgiven right away, draws tears from his eyes by reducing the grand events of history to tales full of good sentiments. Serious and measured, informed and didactic, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> puts his listeners to sleep. ... `` <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> therefore can not win in November except by setting himself off from <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. Expert in the art of nuance, he must prove his firmness. Instinctive partisan of compromise, he must show he can make tough decisions.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 _ The <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- independent -RRB-: `` Mr. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has made much of his managerial image This seems to appeal to the country after Mr. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s hand-off rule _ and its damaging outcome in the Iran-Contra affair. In a <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> presidency, policy is more likely to be managed by the president, and not left in the hands of the Foggy Bottom foreign policy establishment. Mr. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has, after all, done much more managing. His problem is that the appearance belies that fact. Prosperity at home ought also to be a strong card for Mr. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. The fact that after last October's Black Monday the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy did not plunge into a recession or soar with inflation can be seen as a victory for the management of the economy. But American confidence in a prosperous fugure is not strong. Mr. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> can claim to be able to do better, and lumber the vice president with some of the less attractive economic leftovers of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> years. ... <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is not built for presidential campaigning. He has no clear saleable identity. He is not quick. He is not even consistenly clear. ... But he does understand the dangers of the world in which he aspires for leadership. From here that is no small thing in his favor.
</TEXT>
