<HEAD>White House Marks 25th Anniversary of US-Soviet Hotline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> relaxed at his mountaintop ranch, the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> marked the 25th anniversary Tuesday of the U.S.-Soviet hot line intended to reduce the risk of accidental war. During the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, a rapid facsimile capability was added to the Teletype system previously set up to provide instant communication between <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. `` Such measures complement our efforts to negotiate deep, equitable and effectively verifiable reductions in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet nuclear arsenals,'' the White House said in a statement. `` Although used infrequently, the hot line has permitted <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> presidents to communicate with Soviet leaders to reduce the risk of conflict which might result from accident, miscalculation or misunderstanding,'' the statement said. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the president and Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> went horseback riding Tuesday in warm, sunny weather at their ranch north of here. As usual, he said, the president also took care of routine paperwork and chopped some wood.
