<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALLIANCE, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A fund-raising idea to help repair a 50-year-old fountain generated a cascade of coins totalling nearly $ 19,000. About 5,000 people lined up Sunday to place coins, mainly quarters, on masking tape laid by volunteers for 11 blocks along Box Butte Avenue to the fountain. On Monday, <PERSON> Eva </PERSON> <PERSON> Knight </PERSON> said the official total for the Coins for the Fountain drive was $ 18,911.83, but said additional pledges would help fund-raisers to exceed their $ 20,000 goal. Now, said City Parks Superintendent <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaughnessy </PERSON>, the next step is to get estimates for the work. Mrs. <PERSON> Knight </PERSON> is already planning the fountain's lighting ceremony for next May.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEEKONK, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the comics, <PERSON> Superman </PERSON> may leap tall buildings. But <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Wooten </PERSON>, who bills himself the world's strongest man, moves them. <PERSON> Wooten </PERSON>, 40, pulled a 14-ton mobile home atop a flatbed truck about 100 yards across the <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island-Massachusetts </LOCATION> border Monday. The feat took about one minute. When it was done, a red-faced <PERSON> Wooten </PERSON> said, `` It was a little easier than I thought. I think I could have almost gone for two houses.'' <PERSON> Wooten </PERSON>, 6-foot-1 and 274 pounds, said he considers himself to be one of the last old-time strong men, the type who `` uses entertainment to show his strength.''
</TEXT>
