<HEAD>U.S. Accuses Soviets of Violating U.N. Accords on Afghanistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> accused the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> on Tuesday of violating its <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> pullout agreement by using Soviet-based airplanes in bombings against U.S.-backed guerrillas. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is also concerned about the redeployment of Soviet units in support of Afghan government forces fighting for control of the northern city of <LOCATION> Kanduz </LOCATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON>. The Soviets, who withdrew their forces from <LOCATION> Kunduz </LOCATION> in recent weeks, returned with artillery and troops to bolster the government forces, she said. The Soviet troops initially were withdrawn from <LOCATION> Kunduz </LOCATION>, about 30 miles from the Soviet border, as part of a 50-percent reduction of the Soviet presence, in compliance with the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accords. The agreement, signed last April by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and co-guaranteed by both superpowers, calls for a total Soviet pullout by Feb. 15, 1989. The Soviets appear to be using airplanes based inside the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to carry out the aerial bombardments around <LOCATION> Kunduz </LOCATION> in support of the ground forces, Mrs. <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said. `` In our view, the use of the Soviet aircraft coming from inside the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> are a violation of the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> Accords,'' she said. The redeployment of Soviet troops from other parts of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Kunduz </LOCATION> is not viewed as violation, Mrs. <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> added. The pact which brings about an end to more than eight years of Soviet occupation is not in any danger of unraveling, she said. `` We fully expect the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to adhere to the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accords,'' she said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has `` raised the issue of Soviet compliance'' with the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Good Offices Mission which monitors the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> agreement. The Soviets, for their part, have complained to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> body about <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s continued arming of the U.S.-backed <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has said it will continue supplying <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> with weapons for the <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> as long as the Soviets continue arming the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government. The battle for <LOCATION> Kunduz </LOCATION> is viewed as a test of the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> goverment's ability to overcome the <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> once the Soviet pullout is completed. Some analysts believe the government will fall without its Soviet backers and the seven major <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> groups will vie for control of the country among themselves. Despite claims by the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government that it has wrested control of <LOCATION> Kunduz </LOCATION> from the <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION>, the authorities have refused requests by Western reporters to visit the city, Mrs. <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said. The government is flying five planeloads of food and ammunition into <LOCATION> Kunduz </LOCATION> daily to resupply its troops in the continuous fighting, she added. The Soviets are using artillery to back the government troops rather than committing any infantry to the battle, Mrs. <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said. The Soviet involvement in <LOCATION> Kunduz </LOCATION> will likely be raised next week in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> at a meeting between Undersecretary of State <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Armacost </PERSON> and Deputy Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Yuli </PERSON> <PERSON> Vorontsov </PERSON>. Mrs. <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said the two men would meet Sept. 1 and 2 for their third discussion of regional issues in the past 18 months. Other areas on the agenda are the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, she said.
</TEXT>
