<HEAD>Bennett's Farewell Report: Elementary Schools Lack Good Curricula</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, in his final report as education secretary, said Tuesday that <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> elementary school pupils need stronger doses of math, science and literary classics, as well as foreign languages starting in the fourth grade. Students are willing and teachers are `` for the most part good and capable,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said, but too many schools suffer from defective curricula. At a news conference, he released a 61-page report, `` <ORGANIZATION> James </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Madison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>: A Curriculum for American Students,'' summarizing his views of what should be taught to the 32 million youngsters enrolled in kindergarten through the eighth grade in 81,000 elementary and junior high schools. The report is a sequel to a model high school guide entitled `` <ORGANIZATION> James </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Madison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>,'' which <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> wrote last year. He quipped that the latest report might be called `` <ORGANIZATION> Little </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jimmy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Madison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>.'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said he still believes, as he concluded in a 1986 report, that elementary schools are `` in pretty good shape'' and `` face fewer and less severe problems than now plague our high schools.'' By some measures, he said, achievement in the elementary grades stands `` at its highest level in three decades.'' But American youngsters still have an `` insufficient grasp of basic school subjects, and they lag well behind their foreign counterparts,'' he said. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said the culprits include: _ Dull texts that make reading a chore instead of a joy _ `` Dismal'' social studies courses that start teaching children about self-development when they are more interested in dinosaurs and space. _ Math courses that rely on drone-like, repetitive work books <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> has no authority to require any school to adopt his ideas. By law, his department is barred from attempting to impose any curriculum on state and local school officials. `` I wish I had gone to <ORGANIZATION> James </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Madison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sava </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Principals </ORGANIZATION>. To meet such a rich curriculum standard, <PERSON> Sava </PERSON> said, schools need better textbooks, better prepared teachers and more authority to manage their own affairs. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said his model is `` a statement of goals,'' not `` a monolithic program to be uniformly imposed or slavishly followed.'' He laid down a broad outline of topics to be covered in seven subjects: English, social studies, mathematics, science, foreign language, fine arts and physical and health education. His reading lists range from the tales of <LOCATION> Pippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Longstocking </LOCATION> and Mrs. <PERSON> Piggle-Wiggle </PERSON> for the early grades to `` The Red Badge of Courage,'' `` Kon-Tiki'' and `` <PERSON> Alice </PERSON>'s Adventures in Wonderland'' for older pupils. `` Maybe a third of our schools are doing this or approaching this,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said, but even some of those schools do n't offer an enriched curriculum to all their pupils. `` If there's a crucial point here, it's the fourth grade,'' he said. `` We see a fourth-grade slump in reading ... math and science.'' He said less than two-thirds of each school day is spent on academics. Even accounting for lunch and recess, he said, `` something like 20 percent ca n't be accounted for at all.'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, who is leaving his <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> post on Sept. 20, said his suggestions include American history in each of the first five grades, world history and geography in sixth and seventh grades, and world geography and American government in eighth grade. He would have all youngsters take either algebra or pre-algebra by eighth grade, biology in seventh grade and some chemistry and physics in eighth grade. Foreign language instruction should start no later than fourth grade, he said. The report profiles seven schools as models of strong elementary curricula. They are <ORGANIZATION> Meridith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Magnet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> in </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Miller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Junior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Blaine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Blaine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>; School No. 59, Science Magnet, in <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> LaSalle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Language </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patrick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Maryette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Stilwell </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Okla. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said he will <ORGANIZATION> Miller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Junior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> on Wednesday Then he said he will speak Thursday on behalf of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign at <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, where <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is expected to discuss education. `` I want to bring a little sunlight to that discussion,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said. Copies of `` <ORGANIZATION> James </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Madison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>'' can be purchased for $ 2.50 each from the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Printing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> 20402.
