<HEAD>Judge Blocks HUD Sale Of Foreclosed Homes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge temporarily blocked the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday from selling foreclosed single-homes across the nation to the highest bidder. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> said his temporary restraining order would remain in effect until Sept. 14 while Judge <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Gasch </PERSON>, who has jurisdiction over the case, schedules further deliberation. <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> said, `` Clearly, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> did not comply with -LRB- housing laws -RRB-.'' He said challengers of the sales would `` likely be successful on the merits.'' He said his order would apply nationwide, but would not affect <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> sales previously entered into with buyers. The suit was brought by a coalition of advocates for the homeless as part of a broader effort to force the federal government to make the federal government's inventory of 47,000 foreclosed houses available to the homeless. <PERSON> Florence </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagman </PERSON> <PERSON> Roisman </PERSON>, representing the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Project </ORGANIZATION>, said the restraining order was sought because <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> planned to sign contracts to sell 170 homes in the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, D. C., metropolitan area on Wednesday. Last week, the project blocked <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> from selling 200 homes in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> accepted the project's arguments that <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> had violated the Homeless Assistance Act of 1987, requiring <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> to survey all federal buildings and properties to `` identify which ... are suitable to assist the homeless.'' The project also said the legislation stipulates that <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> must then make properties in excess of the agency's need available to the homeless. <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> also violated the National Housing Act, which calls for `` the realization as soon as feasible of the goal of a decent home and a suitable living environment for every American family.'' `` We do n't want <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> to sell off these units to speculators and investors,'' said <PERSON> Roisman </PERSON>. `` They have 47,000 units available. Even if they had 80,000, it would be a drop in the bucket. There are 800,000 families on a waiting list for housing around the country.'' <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Irwin </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> attorney representing <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>, said there is no need for the court to block any house auctions. `` There is a continuing recycling of houses into and out of the <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> inventory,'' he said. Under the restraining order, <PERSON> Irwin </PERSON> said, `` The houses will remain vacant. They will be the subject of vandalism and there will be a loss of property values, depending on the length of the suit.'' <PERSON> Roisman </PERSON> said the houses do not have to remain vacant because, in just the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> area, there are 700 families with 2,500 children living in hotels and motels. `` They would be very happy to move into a home,'' she said.
