<HEAD>Parliament Passes Tough Law on Journalists Who Write Defamatory
Stories</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NILOVA ROY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Parliament on Tuesday enacted legislation that could mean prison sentences of up to five years for journalists who write defamatory articles. Opposition leaders said the bill was motivated by a government dogged by corruption scandals. The Defamation Bill 1988, piloted by the federal government, was passed by a voice vote amid strong resistance from opposition political parties, Indian news agencies said. Members from opposition parties walked out to protest the bill they called `` draconian,'' and designed to `` muzzle the press,'' according to the <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> news agency. A walkout is the strongest form of protest available in parliamentary procedure. The news agency said they objected to a clause that says, `` Where any matter which is grossly indecent or scurrilous or is intended for blackmail, is published in any newspaper, periodical or circular, the author of such matter and the printer, publisher and editor of such newspaper, periodical or circular shall be punishable with imprisonment for a term ... which may extend to five years.'' Opposition parliamentarians resisted the bill because it seeks to cover any imputation of criminal offence against an individual as aggravated defamation, <ORGANIZATION> PTI </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> Janata </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Madhu </PERSON> <PERSON> Dandavate </PERSON> said the government wanted the bill passed to protect itself from the scandals that have surfaced since 1987. Most allege that kickbacks from various defense purchases have been accepted by top government officers and officials of Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> party. <PERSON> Dandavate </PERSON> said the bill was motivated by a government `` under the shadow of scandals.'' <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chidambaram </PERSON>, the minister of State for Home Affairs who introduced the bill Monday, denied the charge. He said the government did not intend to curb the press, but intended to ensure that a person's privacy and honor were not destroyed. `` I will defend until my death the right of newspapers to publish what is truth,'' he said. `` But the right must be to publish only the truth. Investigations by journalists must lead to facts and not to insinuations and innuendos.''
