45 more days, a period that ends Thursday. <PERSON> Aronica </PERSON> said during Tuesday's hearing that his office would ask <PERSON> Kenkel </PERSON> to extend the sealing of those documents. In his ruling, <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> said <PERSON> Kenkel </PERSON> was wrong to decide the search warrants and inventories of what was seized at the three homes should be unsealed, but that applications for the warrants and affidavits supporting them should not. <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON>, noting that there was no disagreement that the information should eventually be made public, said the real dispute was over timing. He said all the documents should stay sealed the same amount of time.
