<HEAD>Out-of-Court Settlement Reached IN Jackson Video Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former presidential hopeful <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has reached an out-of-court settlement with a company that sold thousands of videotapes of his address to the Democratic National Convention, attorneys said Tuesday. `` Yes, there has been a settlement,'' said <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, an attorney for MPI Home Video. `` But I believe the terms are confidential.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, also refused to discuss the agreement, and both sides refused to say whether it would allow the sale or distribution of more MPI tapes of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s speech. `` The parties have reached an agreement in principle,'' <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> said. `` We hope to wrap it up in the next 10 days or so.'' The settlement avoided a trial, which had been scheduled to begin Tuesday, over whether <ORGANIZATION> MPI </ORGANIZATION> had the right to profit from tapes of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s July 19 speech in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> MPI </ORGANIZATION> sold about 7,500 of the videotapes, at $ 14.95 each, before <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zagel </PERSON>'s temporary order July 29 brought a halt to the sales, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Breisblatt </PERSON>, another attorney for Oak Forest-based MPI. <PERSON> Breisblatt </PERSON> said he did not know exactly how long the videotapes had been on sale before then, but he estimated it was less than week. <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s camp, which had gone to court to block the sales, was pleased with the settlement. <ORGANIZATION> MPI </ORGANIZATION> had contended that the black leader's speech was news and unprotected by copyright law. But <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> argued that the videotapes exploited his name as well as his literary and oratorical skills. He testified at an earlier hearing that <ORGANIZATION> MPI </ORGANIZATION>'s tape, which he did not authorize, hurt his livelihood by limiting the marketability of a videotape of the speech that he planned to sell. <PERSON> Zagel </PERSON>, in his order halting the sales, agreed. `` There is ... more than negligible probability that -LRB- <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> -RRB- earns part of his living ... on his oratory,'' the judge said.
