<FIRST>u w AM-Elementary-Outline     08-30 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Elementary-Outline,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Outline of Bennett's Model Elementary School Curriculum</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bennett-Elementary Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is an overview of Secretary <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>'s suggested elementary school curriculum in seven primary subjects:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ENGLISH</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Kindergarten through Grade 3: Introduction to reading and writing, including phonics, silent and oral reading, basic rules of grammar and spelling, vocabulary, writing and penmanship, composition and library skills. Grades 4 through 6: Introduction to critical reading, including children's literature, book reports, advanced grammar, spelling and vocabulary and composition skills. Grade 7: Survey of elementary grammar and composition. Grade 8: Survey of elementary literary analysis.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SOCIAL STUDIES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 K through 3: Introduction to history, geography and civics -LRB- significant Americans, explorers, native Americans, American holidays, customs and symbols; citizenship and landscape, climate and mapwork -RRB-. Grade 4: <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history to Civil War. Grade 5: <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history since 1865. Grade 6: World history to the Middle Ages. Grade 7: World history from the Middle Ages to 1900. Grade 8: World geography and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> constitutional government.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MATHEMATICS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 K through 3: Introduction to mathematics -LRB- numbers, basic operations, fractions and decimals, rounding, geometric shapes, measurement, bar graphs, estimation and elementary statistics. -RRB- Grades 4-6: Intermediate arithmetic and geometry -LRB- number theory, negative numbers, percentages, exponents, line graphs, the Pythagorean theorem and basic probability -RRB-. Grades 7-8: General math, pre-algebra and algebra -LRB- two of the three -RRB-.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SCIENCE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 K through 3: Introduction to science -LRB- plants and animals, the food chain, the solar system, rocks and minerals, weather, magnets, energy and motion, properties of matter and simple experiments -RRB-. Grade 4: Earth science and other topics. Grade 5: Life science and other topics. Grade 6: Physical science and other topics. Grade 7: Biology. Grade 8: Chemistry and physics.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FOREIGN LANGUAGE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 K through 3: Optional. Grades 4-6: Introduction to foreign language -LRB- basic vocabulary, grammar, reading, writing, conversation and cultural material -RRB-. Grades 7-8: Two years of formal language study strongly recommended -LRB- equivalent to a one-year high school course -RRB-.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FINE ARTS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 K through 3: Music and visual art -LRB- songs, recordings, musical sounds and instruments, painting, craftmaking and visual effects -RRB-. Grades 4-6: Music and visual art -LRB- great composers, musical styles and forms, elementary music theory, great painters, interpretation of art and creative projects. Grades 7-8: Music appreciation and art appreciation -LRB- one semester of each -RRB-.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>PHYSICAL EDUCATION@HEALTH</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 K through 3: Body control, fitness, sports, games and exercises, sportsmanship, safety, hygiene, nutrition and drug prevention education. Grades 4-6: Team and individual sports, first aid, drug prevention education and appropriate sex education. Grades 7-8: Strategy in team sports, gymnastics, aerobics, self-assessment for health, drug prevention and sex education.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
