<HEAD>US, Soviets Verify Claims of Each Medium-Range Nuclear Arsenal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> have completed initial, 60-day inspections under the Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces treaty detecting any apparent discrepancies in their claimed arsenals, defense sources said Tuesday. `` The numbers matched,'' said one Pentagon official, referring to the number of nuclear missiles stored at various military installations inside the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact countries. `` And they verified our numbers, too.'' The first 60 days of compliance with the treaty signed by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> last December ended Monday when the superpowers completed all authorized inspections. The so-called baseline inspections were intended to allow each country to verify the number and location of medium-range and shorter range nuclear weapons in each arsenal before their destruction begins under the INF treaty. American inspectors had to visit 133 Soviet weapons facilities at 115 locations during the two-month period. The Soviets had to inspect 31 facilities at 26 sites in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The treaty, which the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> ratified earlier this summer, calls for the elimination within three years of all American and Soviet land-based missiles with ranges of 300 to 3,400 miles. The treaty covers 859 nuclear-armed missiles on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> side, compared with 1,831 on the Soviet side. <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> refused to discuss details of the inspections Tuesday but told reporters: `` I have not seen any reports of problems with regard to the baseline inspections.'' `` We completed our baseline inspections and they completed theirs,'' said Cmdr. <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Pease </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s on-site inspection agency `` The Soviets were very flexible, very professional and very knowledgeable about the treaty, which facilitated our inspections,'' <PERSON> Pease </PERSON> said. `` Both sides knew the terms of the treaty and worked in a professional manner together.'' Under the treaty, both sides next will be entitled to conduct 20 short-notice inspections over the next year at selected military facilities. In addition, permanent inspection teams are on duty at Soviet and American missile plants to guard against cheating, and inspectors from both countries will be able to observe the actual destruction of missiles. The Soviets are now operating `` elimination'' _ or destruction _ programs for missiles and launchers at five different sites, <PERSON> Pease </PERSON> said. In addition, the <LOCATION> Russians </LOCATION> plan within the next week or two to begin destroying up to 100 SS-20 missiles by launching them without their warheads. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will begin destroying the medium-range missiles in its arsenal on Sept. 8 by firing some solid-fuel rockets used in Pershing II missiles at the <ORGANIZATION> Longhorn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ammunition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plant </ORGANIZATION> near <LOCATION> Marshall </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>.
