<HEAD>Biddings Enters Innocent Plea, More Indictments Expected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH GRACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man suspected in 60 rapes pleaded innocent Tuesday to a 21-count indictment charging him with raping and kidnapping five women and assaulting a sixth. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Biddings </PERSON>, 34, of <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, appeared handcuffed before <LOCATION> Franklin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Common Pleas Judge <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Reda </PERSON>. No trial date was set. Biddings, a former restaurant dishwasher, was indicted Friday for allegedly abducting his victims, who included a 12-year-old girl, handcuffing and raping them from 1986 to March 1988. He was arrested after the parents of a 24-year-old rape victim spent more than a year pursuring her attacker. The victim's mother stood at the same east-side bus stop where her daughter was attacked in June 1987 and acted as a decoy while her armed husband waited nearby. The woman was attacked on Aug. 5, but her husband scared off the assailant and gave police the license number of the attacker's vehicle Biddings was arrested three days later. Biddings is suspected of being the `` handcuff rapist,'' a term that refers to the use of handcuffs in early attacks and later was attributed to the same man over four years. The indictment said Biddings had been convicted of rape in <LOCATION> Summit </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> in 1973 and served a jail term on the charge. In all, he was indicted on 12 counts of rape, six counts of kidnapping, two counts of aggravated robbery and one count of felonious assault. Two of Biddings' sisters were in the courtroom Tuesday but refused to talk to reporters after the hearing. `` They're upset,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Erlenbach </PERSON>, Bidding's attorney. `` But they're sticking by him.'' Biddings himself is upset by the charges, because he does not understand the terminology in the indictments, said <PERSON> Erlenbach </PERSON>, who was hired by the defendant's family. `` He does not understand a lot about it,'' he said. `` But he has maintained his innocence to me all along.'' County Prosecutor <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said last week he expects more indictments against Biddings and that he would present further evidence to the grand jury this week. Biddings is being held in lieu of $ 750,000 bond. Meanwhile, the 24-year-old victim urged other rape victims to report their complaints. `` I want victims to know that they have to come forward. That's the only reason I'm talking about this right now They have to come forward,'' the woman said in a copyright story in Tuesday's <ORGANIZATION> Columbus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dispatch </ORGANIZATION> She told the newspaper she has agreed with police not to discuss specifics of the attack until after Biddings is tried.
