<HEAD>Nuclear Weapons Test At Nevada Site</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YUCCA FLAT, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A nuclear weapon was detonated Tuesday at the <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> Test Site, 13 days after Soviet scientists monitored another <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> test at the same site in a historic breakthrough in international relations. Two Soviet scientists were still on site at the time of Tuesday's blast, but were not involved in monitoring the test. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> scientists are in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and will monitor a test there Sept. 14. Tuesday's test measured 4.9 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale of ground motion at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Earthquake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Golden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo </LOCATION>. The test, code-named Bullfrog, was conducted at 11 a.m. PDT and produced a `` very distinct rocking motion'' in a control center 10 miles from ground zero, according to <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Yoerg </PERSON>. The test was not pre-announced, as are larger tests at the desert site. The <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the shot had an explosive force of less than 150 kilotons, the limit under treaties signed in 1974 and 1976. The device was buried in a 1,600-foot shaft at <LOCATION> Yucca </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Flat </LOCATION>, 85 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION>. It was the 10th announced shot this year and the 685th announced since testing began in <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> in January 1951. The most recent previous test was Kearsarge, which was monitored by Soviet scientists as part of tests aimed at developing a method of confirming treaty compliance. Tuesday's test was conducted by <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Livermore </PERSON> <PERSON> Laboratory </PERSON> and was weapons related, Ms. <PERSON> Yoerg </PERSON> said. She said three protesters were at the gates of the sprawling desert site when the test was conducted, but they were more than 40 miles from ground zero. Ms. <PERSON> Yoerg </PERSON> said no radioactive material escaped from Tuesday's test The ground above the device subsided an hour after the blast, she said. That is considered a good sign by <ORGANIZATION> DOE </ORGANIZATION> officials because it indicates the radioactive materials have been permanently sealed underground.
