<TEXT>
 Here is a brief outline of forest fire conditions Tuesday in the Western states:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WYOMING:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Eight forest fires are burning in <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> with four in the surrounding national forests in northwestern <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>. The Yellowstone Fires, some of which have spread out into the forests, had charred about 450,000 acres of the 2.2 million-acre park. The largest fire outside <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> Mink </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> fire, covers 107,960 acres of the <ORGANIZATION> Bridger-Teton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION>. Yellowstone officials said they have spent $ 54.4 million fighting fires and about 8,400 firefighters, including hundreds of Army soldiers, are working in the area. Unusually dry weather and a rash of lightning storms opened the fire season early this year, with the first Yellowstone fires reported in June.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MONTANA:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Eight major fires had burned 177,000 acres of <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> forests Tuesday, including two that erupted into serious threats overnight. They ranged in size up to 41,000 acres. Four, totaling 128,700 acres, were in designated wilderness areas, including one that had spread into Yellowstone National Park. Firefighters were gaining the upper hand on most, however, and no populated areas were threatened.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>IDAHO:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 More than 2,500 firefighters, backed up by dozens of National Guardsmen, were on the lines against the worst of 17 fires burning over 70,000 acres from the <ORGANIZATION> Panhandle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> to the <ORGANIZATION> Caribou </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> on the <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> border. No structures were in imminent danger, but crews were protecting summer homes from the 16,000-acre Battle Axe wilderness fire northeast of <PERSON> Challis </PERSON>, a communications site from the 330-acre West <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> fire in the <ORGANIZATION> Clearwater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> east of <LOCATION> Lewiston </LOCATION> and ranches from the 5,000-acre <LOCATION> Trail </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> fire near the <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> border in the Caribou. Some $ 3 million in commercial timber has been lost, mostly to the 7,400-acre Eagle Bar fire near <LOCATION> Hells </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canyon </LOCATION> on the <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> border. The terrain is parched by a second straight year of drought, and Gov. <PERSON> Cecil </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrus </PERSON> has put the entire state under an extreme fire emergency.
