<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Many Iranian and <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> prisoners of war fear persecution if they return home and some Iraqis may riot against repatriation, say <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> investigators who visited their camps. Prisoner camps in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> are ruled internally by zealous Iraqi POWs who have switched their loyalty to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> experts said in a report scheduled for release Thursday. The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> saw a copy of the report Tuesday. `` In each camp we visited -LRB- in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> -RRB-, there were fanatical, hysterical and sometimes violent demonstrations by the prisoners, who were assembled inside, along the barbed wire fences,'' the three <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> experts reported. Iraqi prisoners shouted slogans denouncing <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s President <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> and the superpowers, and praised Islam and <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, the investigators said, and rallies were so fervid at the <LOCATION> Arak </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Davoudieh </PERSON> camps that they could not enter safely. About half the prisoners participated in each case and clearly were under the influence of 10-20 percent or the group, the report said. The team visited the camps in late July and early August. Camp committees provide religious and political instruction and persuasion under the name `` spiritual guidance,'' the experts said, and `` to us, it is indistinguishable from mental pressure.'' In the camps in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> holding Iraqi prisoners, the team concluded, `` There is a risk that riots may break out, for example in the moment when transfer is to take place with a view to registration and repatriation.'' In the camps in <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, the Iranian POWs were more orderly and Iraqi authorities maintained control, but many prisoners also appeared hesitant about going home after the 8-year-old war. `` The majority, however, seemed inclined to return to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, provided they were given effective gurantees that they would not be subject to persecution on their return,'' the report said. `` In the absence of such guarantees, however, their future looks gloomy.'' <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> listed 46,098 POWs in its camps but many new prisoners had not been registered so the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> team decided the number could be about 70,000. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> furnished a list of 18,139 POWs as of Aug. 1, but <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> authorities told the team many new prisoners had not been registered. The investigators decided the total could be about 35,000. Conditions in the camps of both sides `` are, on the whole, acceptable, although it might be desirable to have them further improved on some points,'' the report said. Pro-Khomeini Iraqis dominating <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s camps reject Western institutions, including the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, which registers prisoners of war and looks after their welfare, the investigators said. Because they view the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> as ineffective and dominated by the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, many have refused to register with it, complicating the repatriation process. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> team also found, however, that some Iraqi POWs were never given a chance by Iranian authorities to register with the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> or were dissuaded by the pro-Khomeini Iraqi prisoners. According to the report, Iranian authorities cooperated in verifying the whereabouts of `` nearly all'' 7,327 Iraqi POWs registered by the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> before 1984 who were listed as missing, showing them to be safe and alive in or out of POW camps. <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> authorities cooperated in tallying about 25,000 Iranian Kurds, 30,000 Iranian Arabs, and more than 300 other Iranians listed by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> as missing. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> said they sought asylum and were in three refugee camps. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> team found the facilities similar to POW camps, surrounded by barbed wire, but the residents had relative freedom of movement. More than 200 POWs held by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> are from <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION>, the team said. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has called them `` mercenaries'' but has promised to free them. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> have accused each other of the torture and maltreatment of POWs. In <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> team said, `` We never saw any direct evidence of atrocities, torture or beating; but from the conversations we had with some prisoners we can not dismiss allegations that such acts have occurred.'' In <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s Camp Number Nine in the <LOCATION> Ramadi </LOCATION> region, the team found abuse that `` did not seem typical of Iraqi camps at large.'' Members of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> team were Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Rene </PERSON> <PERSON> Bats </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Wolfram </PERSON> <PERSON> Karl </PERSON>, an Austrian professor of international law, and <PERSON> Torkel </PERSON> <PERSON> Opsahl </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, also a professor of international law. They visited <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s camps July 23-30 and the Iraqi camps July 31-Aug. 5
