<HEAD>Stress May Be Factor In Bizarre String Of Scientists' Deaths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stress can not be ruled out as the cause of some of the mysterious deaths and disappearances in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s defense and electronics industry, a union said Tuesday. The Manufacturing, <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> said it recently surveyed technical, managerial and professional staff in six companies and found many experience high stress levels and fewer than 4 percent are happy in their jobs. Sixteen men employed in defense or security work _ including seven who worked for <ORGANIZATION> Marconi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> or its related companies _ have died in unusual circumstances since 1982 Many of the men died in unexplained, even bizarre circumstances. Most deaths resembled suicides, although only two have been so ruled. `` Stress can not be ruled out as a contributing factor in the spate of Marconi deaths,'' said <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Brooke </PERSON>, the union's national officer. `` The people who have died were overwhelmingly in responsible positions. The electronics industry is highly competitive and the defense side has undergone an immense change over the last five years. The screw has been tightened and more and more pressure has been piled on,'' he said. <PERSON> Brooke </PERSON> called for employers in the industry to `` treat people at work like people and not numbers'' in an attempt to ease the pressure. The union surveyed employees at <ORGANIZATION> Marconi </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Racal </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Plessey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. PLC, <PERSON> Ferranti </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Philips </ORGANIZATION> and Thorn <ORGANIZATION> EMI </ORGANIZATION>, all major electronics companies with a sizeable involvement in government defense work It found only 3.5 percent said they were happy and fulfilled in their work, and 41 percent said they were dissatisfied with their work environment to the point where they said it affected their home life and health. Nearly one-quarter said they often found it difficult to relax and the same proportion complained of bringing their problems home and of feeling constantly drained and lethargic. The survey results are based on 500 replies to 2,000 questionnaires distributed to union members and non-members in the industry. The British government has said the spate of deaths and disappearances is odd but has insisted the frequency of deaths is a coincidence and has rejected calls for an inquiry. The string of deaths dates from March 1982 when <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowden </PERSON>, a 45-year-old expert on supercomputers and computer-controlled aircraft, drove his car off a highway and down a railway embankment. Police said he had been drinking, but friends denied it. Among the succeeding deaths was a computer systems analyst for a <ORGANIZATION> Marconi </ORGANIZATION> unit who killed himself by tying a rope to a tree, looping the other end around his neck and then driving off in his car at high speed. A computer expert for Easams, a Marconi sister company, drove his car, its trunk loaded with tanks of gasoline, into a vacant restaurant and burned to death. Three of the men died in or under their cars in fume-filled garages, and a digital communications expert fell from a hotel room in the <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> after expressing fear for his life. Most recently, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferry </PERSON> was found electrocuted Aug. 24 in his apartment at the headquarters of <ORGANIZATION> Marconi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Frimley </LOCATION>, 35 miles southwest of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. The former army brigadier, 60, was an assistant marketing director with special responsibility for liaison with the armed forces. His widow said the pressure of his secret work may have contributed to his death.
