hich was established with the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> and Democratic party chairmen. The League of Women Voters, sponsor of fall debates in the last three presidential elections, has proposed a debate Sept. 8 in <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, followed by debates Oct. 6 in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>; Oct. 23 in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>; and Nov. 1 in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. League president <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Neuman </PERSON> offered to help mediate, and said the lingering dispute is evidence of the political parties' `` inexperience in debates sponsorship. After <LOCATION> Annapolis </LOCATION> on Sept. 14, the commission wants other debates on Sept. 25 in <LOCATION> Winston-Salem </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>; Oct. 11 in <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb </LOCATION>.; and Oct. 27 in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION> debate could be for the vice presidential candidates. In 1984, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> met Democrat <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> in two debates, on Oct. 7 and Oct. 21, and a third debate was held Oct. 11 between their running mates. In 1980, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> met in one debate, on Oct. 28. In 1976, President <PERSON> Ford </PERSON> met <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> in three debates, and their running mates also held a debate.
