<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>' labor leaders embraced a federal judge's ruling Tuesday that blocked layoffs of 4,000 employees, although it allows the company to go ahead with service cutbacks. `` We're please at this ruling. It will save 4,000 jobs -LRB- and it rules that -RRB- the proposed furloughing is illegal,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON>, president of District 100 of the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s largest with 12,000 workers <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON>, flight attendants' leader <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> and pilots local vice chairman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vician </PERSON> talked to reporters at the <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> hall just off the <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> as their attorneys studied the 50-page opinion by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Barrington </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Eastern, while satisfied that <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> will allow the closing of its <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> hub and the elimination of 140 flights, said it will appeal his decision that the company can not make mass layoffs without bargaining with its unions. <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> called the decision `` an opportunity'' for <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> to show he is more than `` the No 1 union-buster.'' `` Here now is a chance for him to change his style. The ball is in <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>'s court,'' <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> said. He and the other union leaders expressed willingness to meet with management to discuss cost-cutting measures that preserve jobs. `` We're not here as laborers trying to direct the business of the airline. We're trying to protect jobs,'' <PERSON> Vician </PERSON> said. Ms. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> said the flight attendants were still willing to offer a job-sharing and leave plan, rejected earlier by management, to save jobs and money. Eastern spokeswoman <PERSON> Paula </PERSON> <PERSON> Musto </PERSON> said she could n't comment on the unions' interpretation of the opinion. The union leaders stressed <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>'s findings of fact that <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>, which took over Miami-based <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> two years ago, has been antagonistic toward unions, tried to spin off assets such as the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> shuttle service and has worsened <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s financial problems by using <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> resources to pay for its own sale, taking a non-interest $ 16 million note from <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and taking a $ 6 million annual management fee from Eastern. `` In short, the record shows that <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> has served as a lending institution to meet the needs of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- the non-union carrier also owned by Houston-based <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-,'' the opinion said. `` It confirmed what we've been saying,'' <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> said. `` This is a federal judge. It's not the unions anymore or our consultants talking.'' Eastern is cutting 140 flights and service from 14 cities, while reducing its <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> hub from 53 to six flights and non-hub status. Ms. <PERSON> Musto </PERSON> said the company has n't determined what it will do with the protected employees.
