<HEAD>Panama Participates In U.S.-Backed Drug Sweep</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-International-Drugs, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> was among the 30 nations that participated in a U.S.-backed drug crackdown, even though the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> brought economic sanctions against the country because of drug charges against its military leader. Colombian narcotics officials, meanwhile, were skeptical about the success of the joint drug crackdown. They said no major traffickers were arrested in the operations from Aug. 1-28 and the amounts of drugs seized were not impressive. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> had encouraged the 30 countries to step up enforcement and specifically to cooperate in cross-border raids, mostly in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, during August. <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> head <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawn </PERSON> praised the anti-drug campaign and said it showed that international cooperation could eliminate sanctuaries for drug traffickers who tried to evade capture by going to other countries. Lawn and other representatives made brief statements during a meeting with reporters, but journalists were not allowed to ask questions. The <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> meeting coincided with a report in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on the results of the operations by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> that the raids led to more than 1,200 arrests, the seizure of 11 tons of cocaine and the destruction of 244 tons of marijuana, 118,000 coca plants and 13 cocaine laboratories. The Panamanian delegate to the <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> meeting, Lt. Col. <PERSON> Nivaldo </PERSON> <PERSON> Madrinan </PERSON>, said in his statement that <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> participated in the program even though it is `` suffering the greatest aggression in its history.'' He did not specifically mention the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sanctions. <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s military leader, Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, was indicted in February by two federal grand juries in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> that accused him of drug trafficking. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> imposed economic sanctions against <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> after <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> refused to resign and leave the country. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, commander of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION>, controls the civilian government. <PERSON> Madrinan </PERSON> said the month-long drug crackdown in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> produced 96 arrests and the seizure of 4.8 pounds of cocaine, $ 2,084, eight vehicles and eight weapons. Reporters were now allowed to ask who had been arrested. <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> sent delegates to the <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> meeting. Colombian officials, speaking with the condition they not be identified, noted the <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> reported the raids turned up 13 cocaine laboratories and they said more than 13 labs are frequently found in a single week in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> report said that of the 11 tons of cocaine and cocaine base seized, 6.2 tons were found in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> countries. The Colombian officials said that in one raid in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> five years ago more than 10 tons of cocaine and cocaine base were seized. The Colombians also questioned a section of the <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> statement that said the raids were the result of cooperation among the participating countries. They said cross-border operations between <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> were a week late because of border disputes and claimed <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> did virtually nothing during the campaign.
