<HEAD>Officials Allow Only Blacks To Take Test</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 15 whites were turned away Tuesday from a civil service examination for police recruits that was for blacks only, and some complained they were the victims of reverse discrimination. The test was given to 620 black men and women who had signed up to take the test at the Civic Auditorium. The whites, through a mixup, had been told to be at the auditorium too. When they showed up, they were turned away. City officials said the whites never should have been told they could take the test. The city placed an advertisement this summer in The <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times-Union </ORGANIZATION> seeking black applicants only for police recuits because there were no blacks on the list of candidates eligible to enter the police academy. A total of 175 whites who had passed an examination in January were on the list. All the blacks who passed the exam already have entered the academy or are scheduled to enter this fall. <PERSON> Clarence </PERSON> <PERSON> Rease </PERSON>, division chief for recruiting and examining, said the city held the recruiting drive because Sheriff <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON> is committed to hiring more black officers. Currently, there are 900 white officers and about 200 black officers. <PERSON> Rease </PERSON> said he does n't know why whites were allowed to fill out applications to take Tuesday's test. `` My announcements said for blacks only. The applications said for blacks only,'' he said. Three white men who showed up to take the test said they were the victims of reverse discrimination. `` The first thing out of the mouth was, ` White applicants can not take the test today,''' said a man who asked that his name not be used. `` That's discrimination.''
