<HEAD>Criminal Charges to Be Filed if High Court Reinstates Fines</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Another vote ...,' with 2 grafs to UPDATE
with no change in the council's position Tuesday night. INSERTS 1
graf after 10th graf pvs, ``We must ....' to UPDATE with Jesse
Jackson offer to meet with councilmen.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YONKERS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The state agency that has taken over <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION>' finances warned four defiant councilmen Tuesday that unless the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> takes their side, they will be hit with criminal charges. The councilmen, who have stalled a federal judge's order to act on a housing desegregation plan, have appealed both the judge's ruling and asked for a stay of their fines until a decision comes from the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> The councilmen, who personally may have to pay contempt-of-court fines of up to $ 500 a day, and the city, whose fines could go up to $ 1 million daily, applied for stays to <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Justice <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, who often handles such appeals from the Northeast. But a court spokesman said Tuesday afternoon the five applications were turned over to the full court. The spokesman, who asked not to be named, said he could give no indication when the court might rule. For the third time since the contempt finding, the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, at its regular meeting Tuesday night, refused to endorse the desegregation plan, which would approve incentives for 800 units of moderate-income housing throughout the city. In a packed Council chamber, Mayor <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Wasicsko </PERSON> asked if any of the councilmen wanted to change their vote but none of them did. The mayor is required by the contempt ruling to have a weekly vote on the desegregation plan. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Sand </PERSON>, who in 1985 found the city liable for segregating schools and housing for 40 years, held the city in contempt Aug. 2 for failing to approve the housing plan. Sand imposed fines against the city that began at $ 100 a day and doubled daily. The fines were later stayed by a federal appeals court. Besides the personal fines on the four councilmen, Sand also threatened them with jail. On Friday, a federal appeals panel upheld the contempt finding but gave <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> a week to take the case to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> before reinstating the penalties. The panel also capped any daily fine at $ 1 million. The fines are slated to go back into effect Friday; the jailing of the councilmen would come Sunday. Meanwhile, the Rev. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> Tuesday that even if the housing dispute in <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> is not a result of racial discrimination, the city's resistance to the law is unhealthy. `` We must be as intolerant of a class rejection _ because someone is poor _ as we would be of racial or religious bigotry,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. After a meeting with black leaders in <LOCATION> Westchester </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said he would be willing to meet with the four councilmen. Three of the four responded they would be happy to meet with <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, while the fourth said, `` Have him call me.'' At a meeting Tuesday of the <ORGANIZATION> Yonkers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, its chairwoman said she will notify the district attorney that the four councilmen are breaking the law. The state watchdog agency was already in place because of money problems the city had several years ago. `` It's the city councilmen who are defying the law and putting the city's financial profile at risk, who are putting all the citizens of <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> at risk,'' said <PERSON> Gail </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON>, the chairwoman. <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON> labeled the recalcitrant lawmakers `` reprehensible'' for jeopardizing the city financially. Criminal charges should `` give them pause,'' <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON> said of the four, <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Spallone </PERSON>, <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Longo </PERSON>, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Fagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Chema </PERSON>. <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON>'s remarks came a day after Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> said he would initiate removal proceedings and urge the jailing of the councilmen if the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> refused the stay. The financial control board asked City Manager <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> DeLuca </PERSON> to prepare a detailed phase-out plan by Thursday for the gradual elimination of city services.
