<HEAD>Scholars See Moral Issue In Quayle-Vietnam Furor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Religious ethicists say the central moral question about Sen. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s conduct as a young man during the Vietnam War period is whether his actions squared with his attitude. Some see inconsistency between his stated support for the war at that time, while virtually assuring he would n't be involved in it by joining the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> when he faced being drafted. Several theologians said in interviews that <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> as a youth may not have understood the implications then, and that motivations are nebulous, but his course appears equivocal on the surface. The case was termed due for analysis in some ethics courses this fall. `` It borders on hypocrisy, and it's certainly not heroic, but none of us fully takes the consequences of his or her beliefs all the time,'' said the Rev. <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Shinn </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Union Theological Seminary. `` There comes a time when the chips are down that you've got to live up to your convictions and take the costs. But you ca n't get involved in every fight that comes along, even if you believe in it. You muddle through, sit one out.'' <PERSON> Shinn </PERSON>, a teacher of Christian ethics for a quarter century, counseled troubled students during the Vietnam War. He noted some opposed it, paying for it by going to jail, while some supported it and died in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. `` Either way, they paid the costs,'' he said. `` That's what real integrity is. Whether you agree with a person or not, acting with integrity means taking a stand and willingness to suffer for it.'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> says he entered the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> so as to go to law school. `` I did not join to avoid service in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>,'' he says. He says he `` supported the goals of fighting communism in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'' and disliked the `` no-win policy aspect.'' Ethicists say the issue was not his entering the Guard, which many war opponents did to avoid the draft, and not mainly whether he used family influence to do it, but whether he practiced what he preached. `` If you believe one way, you have to act consistently with it or your ethical stance collapses,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> psychologist <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Loyola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Th Rev. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>, who teaches <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> ethics at <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seminary </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, said if <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> was `` really honest about it, he would come clean that he was dodging the draft. `` The real issue is one of honesty and straightforwardness. If he supported <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and then tried to get out of it, it was hypocritical to the core. It was not a matter of conscience, but of expediency.'' Moral philosopher <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> said <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s course raises `` a small question mark about his integrity.'' `` But it's relatively minor,'' <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> said. `` It's not worth all the hullabaloo. I have doubts about how strong his convictions were on <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. Maybe he should have sought to go there and help the cause. `` But he chose not to for reasons we do n't fully understand. You ca n't judge guilt from the outside, but should give a person the benefit of the doubt. Young men make mistakes. We're all entitled to be wrong sometimes. `` He may now regret it.'' <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> moral theologian <PERSON> Germain </PERSON> <PERSON> Grisez </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mary </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Emmitsburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, said it is not clearly inconsistent for people to favor `` fighting a war, but not particularly want to be in it themselves. `` Very often people want their dirty work done, but do n't want to do it themselves. I'm not sure it's wrong, and not sure it's all right either. It's a question of fairness, of being unfair to other people by shirking. `` It's clearly not heroic character, but that does not mean it's immoral. Rabbi <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Schindler </PERSON>, an ethical scholar and president of the <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hebrew </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congregations </ORGANIZATION>, said there `` seems to be quite a distance'' between what <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> `` professes and what he does. `` Obviously one should not proclaim what he fails to do. If his words belie his deeds, he becomes a hypocrite. Actions should come close to ideals. Yet nobody's actions reflect the ideal totally. Everybody fails it sometimes.'' The Rev. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Burtchaell </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Notre </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dame </ORGANIZATION> said people may see <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s `` strong view of the war as in conflict with his public action ... I do n't think he's profound enough to be hypocritical.'' Episcopal moral theologian <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Duke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> said `` the meaning of actions and statements always have to be interpreted. I do n't know how to say his are consistent, but I reckon that he does. `` Typically there is more than one way to look at it.''
</TEXT>
