<HEAD>Briton in Competition to Become West's First Chess Millionaire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lying on the floor in his north <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> apartment, <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Speelman </PERSON> shook his head, smiled, and parried the suggestion he might become the West's first chess millionaire. On Aug. 23, the 31-year-old grandmaster became the first player to reach the semifinals of the World Chess Championship, which puts him only two victories away from a 1990 title match with the reigning world champion, <PERSON> Garri </PERSON> <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. He will not know his semi-finals opponent until the three remaining quarterfinals matches are played in January. No British player has ever reached such an advanced stage of this competition. Ten years ago, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> had no chess grandmasters and chess was far from a big-money competition. But corporate sponsors and paying spectators have put top players in the financial big leagues. The loser of the 1990 world championship duel will be guaranteed three-eighths of the expected $ 2 million prize fund. The 1987 world face-off between <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Anatoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Seville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, had a winners' pot totaling $ 1.85 million. As an added incentive, the West German computer company <ORGANIZATION> Mephisto </ORGANIZATION> will give 1 million Swiss francs -LRB- $ 637,000 -RRB- to the first Westerner to challenge <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON>. But the 6-foot, 3-inches tall <PERSON> Speelman </PERSON> said in an interview that money `` is not my major consideration.'' For <PERSON> Speelman </PERSON>, chess is an intellectual pursuit and he remains determined not to own a car or television. His 3 -LCB- - to-1 -LCB- victory in the quarterfinals over fellow Briton <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Short </PERSON>, 23, the world's third ranked player and pre-match favorite, netted <PERSON> Speelman </PERSON> a $ 21,250 prize, his biggest ever But critics fear his disarmingly peaceful disposition and non-competitive approach are n't winning ingredients. `` He's got to become less modest,'' said <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Tisdall </PERSON>, an American international master who lives in <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> and served as an adviser to <PERSON> Speelman </PERSON> in the quarterfinals. <PERSON> Speelman </PERSON> admits feeling sorry for his opponents. `` Of course I always want to win, but I do n't want my opponent to lose,'' he said. In contrast to <PERSON> Short </PERSON>, who left school at 16 and once played in a rock-group called `` The Urge,'' or the flamboyant <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON>, who employs a Western business manager, <PERSON> Speelman </PERSON> appears as the stereotype intellectual chess player. Bearded and bespectacled, he studied mathematics at <ORGANIZATION> Oxford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and, after earning his grandmaster title in 1980, took a year's break from the game to learn Russian. <PERSON> Speelman </PERSON> writes poetry and enjoys word games. Competing in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> this year, he was delighted when a friend in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> sent him <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> crossword by facsimile. He has also been involved in political battles. In May 1986, he took part in a demonstration outside <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s Prince <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Theater </PERSON> on the opening night of the musical `` Chess'' to lend support to <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Gulko </PERSON>, a leading Soviet grandmaster, in his campaign to gain exit visas to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> for his family <PERSON> Gulko </PERSON>, who once went on a 40-day hunger strike, received his emigration papers several months later and now lives in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. Last year, <PERSON> Speelman </PERSON> jointly hosted a simultaneous chess exhibition to raise money for medical supplies for <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s Sandinista government <PERSON> Speelman </PERSON> has spent up to six months a year abroad and his knowledge of Russian has helped build friendships. International Master <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> said <PERSON> Speelman </PERSON>'s creativity makes him the `` most difficult of opponents to predict. He first learned the chess moves at age 6. At 13, he won the British under-14 championship and since then his career has been marked by a gradual, but consistent improvement. In 1986, in <LOCATION> Dubai </LOCATION> on the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, he was ranked fifth among <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s grandmasters and played for the <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> team that won the silver medal in the biennial chess Olympiad. In the last two years, however, <PERSON> Speelman </PERSON> said, a `` a quantum jump'' took him to fifth ranked player in the world. He said he does n't know what happened. He just got better. `` Chess is basically scientific but there is also a strong psychological and artistic side,'' he said. `` Because it's so intense, you can reach parts of yourself which you would n't very often, a higher state of mind perhaps.'' On his way to meet <PERSON> Short </PERSON>, <PERSON> Speelman </PERSON> overwhelmed the top <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> player, <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Seirawan </PERSON>, by a score of 4-1 in a six-game match.
</TEXT>
