<HEAD>Pope to Beatify Missionary in Kingdom Encircled by South Africa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THABA BOSIU, Lesotho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 On his visit to this kingdom surrounded by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> will come here to a sacred mountain where a French missionary helped native people threatened by white men more than 100 years ago. Later on during his stop in <LOCATION> Lesotho </LOCATION> on his five-nation tour of southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> Sept. 10-19, the pontiff will beatify the Roman Catholic missionary, the Rev. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON>. At <LOCATION> Thaba </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bosiu </LOCATION> on Sept. 14, the pontiff will meet King <PERSON> Moshoeshoe </PERSON> II on the same spot where King <PERSON> Moshoeshoe </PERSON> I in 1862 first welcomed Christian missionaries to his land, torn by internal violence and threatened by the surrounding white <PERSON> Boers </PERSON>, the settlers of what today is <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON> was one of the missionaries, who traveled through the mountains on horseback wrapped in wool blankets as the Basotho -LRB- the people of <LOCATION> Lesotho </LOCATION> -RRB- still do. <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON> climbed the rocky, natural fortress of <LOCATION> Thaba </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bosiu </LOCATION> _ `` The Mountain of the Night'' in the local language _ several times during the 1865-68 conflict with the white <PERSON> Boers </PERSON>, sneaking past them to bring food and encouragement to the thousands of Basotho crowded onto the top of the 600-foot-high plateau. The missionaries persuaded <PERSON> Moshoeshoe </PERSON> I to seek protection from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s Queen <PERSON> Victoria </PERSON>. As a result, Basutoland, as the area was called, became a British protectorate and was saved from annexation into what was later to become <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Basutoland became independent <LOCATION> Lesotho </LOCATION> in 1966. The 12,134-square-mile kingdom _ about half the size of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> _ has almost no industry, only one-third of its land is arable, and it relies heavily on the earnings of 140,000 Basotho men who work in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, which is not on the pope's itinerary. The pope will beatify <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON> during a Mass at a racetrack near here on Sept. 15 before departing next day for <LOCATION> Swaziland </LOCATION>. The pontiff will not go to the summit of <LOCATION> Thaba </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bosiu </LOCATION>, the royal burial ground, where residents say a large dune of fine, red sand at the summit contains the spirit of the first king, and like him, never leaves the mountaintop. When the dune approaches the edge, upward drafts of wind blow it back. King <PERSON> Moshoeshoe </PERSON> I discovered the mountain refuge in 1824 and gathered feuding, destitute, and some cannibalistic tribes together to found the Basotho nation. He welcomed the missionaries, and spent his last years trying to choose whether to become a Catholic or a Protestant. When he died without making a decision, <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON> wrote, `` I have never felt such great sorrow in my life.'' The present king is Catholic, as are 70,000 other Basotho. Ninety percent of the population of 1,443,853 are <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION>; the rest are animists. <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON> died in 1914, after working for 52 years among the Basotho, establishing schools, a hospital and a church, supervising the printing of books in the Sesotho language and converting <ORGANIZATION> Basotho </ORGANIZATION> to Catholicism. His mission at <ORGANIZATION> Roma </ORGANIZATION> is now run by a French Canadian, the Rev. <PERSON> Gilles </PERSON> <PERSON> Jalbert </PERSON>, who gave up horseback riding a few years ago. He supervised construction of a chapel over <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON>'s grave, chopped down trees and prepared rest quarters for the pope's entourage. He hopes electricity will reach <ORGANIZATION> Roma </ORGANIZATION> by the time the pope does, so the Mass at the nearby sports ground can be amplified. The pope will visit <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON>'s grave, from which local people have been taking dirt for decades to sprinkle on their crops, homes and children to bring good fortune. <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON> is being beatified, the first step toward sainthood, because of the healing of a 6-year-old blind girl in 1928, 14 years after his death. Doctors could n't cure <LOCATION> Florina </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Phakela </LOCATION>, so a priest at the <ORGANIZATION> Roma </ORGANIZATION> mission had a bag of soil from <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON>'s grave tied around her neck and told her mother to pray for nine days. The girl, who died in 1982, told <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> investigators she was visited in the night by a priest who told her she was cured. When she woke in the morning, her sight restored, she went to the mission to thank the priest, but could n't find him. She identified a picture of <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON> as the one who had visited her.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tue PMs, Sept. 6</NOTE>
