<HEAD>Jews and Human Rights Leaders Hail Argentine Anti-Discrimination
Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By OSCAR SERRAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Human rights leaders and Jews are hailing a new law that imposes fines or jail sentences on anyone convicted of discrimination based on race, religion or sex. They call it a significant advance in the protection of civil liberties in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>. `` We think the law has extraordinary social and political significance for Argentine society,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON>, president of the Delegation of Argentine Israelite Associations. `` There was a gap in previous legislation in that there was no penalty for those who did discriminate,'' said <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON>, a medical doctor whose organization is the largest of several that represent the estimated 400,000 Jews in this South American country. <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> Lazara </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> congressman and a leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Permanent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` The law is not solely aimed at anti-Semitism, but also at discrimination based on color or creed, or against the native -LRB- Indian -RRB- communities.'' The legislation was introduced early in 1984 by President <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>, who co-founded and ran the <ORGANIZATION> Permanent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> before he was elected to office in October 1983. His inauguration seven weeks later ended a harsh, nearly eight-year military dictatorship. As reworked and finally approved by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in August, the new law penalizes anyone who `` arbitrarily blocks, obstructs or restricts ... the full exercise ... of fundamental rights and guarantees.'' <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s Constitution of 1853 as amended protects the right to assembly, universal suffrage and freedom of speech and worship, although Roman Catholicism is the country's official religion and only Catholics can hold the nation's presidency and vice presidency. The law punishes by jail up to three years anyone convicted of belonging to an organization that promotes the superiority of one race or color or creed over another. Anyone convicted of a crime or offense committed `` in persecution or hatred of a race, religion or nationality, or with the intent to destroy ... a national, ethnic, racial or religious group,'' could be sentenced to additional fines or prison. The law also requires restitution in cases of property damage. `` Overall, the new law constitutes a vision of the new democracy in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, reflecting the conditions that have existed since the end of the last military dictatorship,'' <PERSON> Lazara </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s century-old tradition of democracy has been tarnished by six military interventions since 1930, including coups that ousted Gen. <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Peron </PERSON> in 1955, two civilian presidents in the 1960s, and <PERSON> Peron </PERSON>'s wife Isabel in 1976. More than 9,000 Argentines, most of them sons and daughters of the middle class, `` disappeared'' and are presumed dead following their arrests in the late 1970s by security forces trying to crush the Montonero urban guerrillas and leftist political opposition in general. Discrimination usually is not overt, but it is pervasive. Darker skinned Argentines of Indian descent, while not barred from white-collar jobs, more commonly are manual laborers. Very few Jews are in the army. Women are paid less than men for doing the same job. Anti-Semitism in recent years has been reflected by the knocking over of Jewish tombstones in cemeteries, the painting of anti-Semitic graffitti on walls and, very infrequently but always intimidating, the setting off of small bombs in the doorways of synagogues. `` We do n't have a very serious problem of discrimination based on religion or race, but there is, in the background, among certain sectors, some anti-Semitism,'' said <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Ignacio </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON>, <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>'s press secretary <PERSON> Angel </PERSON> <PERSON> Grushka </PERSON>, leader of the leftist Federation of Jewish Cultural Entities, said the new law is helpful, but he added tha the wished the acts of discrimination that would invoke the penalties were more precisely spelled out. `` We still have to work very hard on the judicial level to make sure that anti-Semitic actions are punished,'' <PERSON> Grushka </PERSON> said. Anti-discrimination legislation in Argentine law dates to 1949. In 1964, similar legislation that penalized those convicted of discrimination was implemented, but that legislation was revoked by the military government that came to power two years later.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, Sept. 7</NOTE>
