<HEAD>One-Year Anniversary of Weapons Protest Maiming</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the year since he lost his legs trying to block a trainload of munitions, <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Willson </PERSON> has become a symbol of inspiration in the movement for peace in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Hundreds have been stirred to maintain ` round-the-clock protests at the <ORGANIZATION> Concord </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weapons </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Station </ORGANIZATION> since last Sept. 1, the day the slow-moving <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> train, under orders not to stop, rolled over <PERSON> Willson </PERSON> as he sat on the tracks The demonstrators, surrounded by picket signs, sleeping bags and <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flags, stand by as trains and trucks carry weapons across <ORGANIZATION> Port </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION>, which cuts through the base. `` Because of what I chose to do and what the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> chose to do, I'm a symbol and that can be used for good, I think,'' <PERSON> Willson </PERSON>, 47, said this week in an interview at the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Practice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nonviolence </ORGANIZATION>, which he founded with his wife, <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> <PERSON> Rauen </PERSON>. The soft-spoken <PERSON> Willson </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> veteran born on the Fourth of July and raised in a conservative, politically inactive family in <LOCATION> Ashville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, said he's more convinced than ever of the need to campaign for peace and a halt to weapons shipments to Central American nations. `` I do n't think it was a mistake and I do n't regret what I did. I'm sorry the train ran over me and that I lost my legs. It's a drag,'' he said. `` I feel more liberated than ever to speak the truth, so I do n't have any desire or wish to back off,'' he said. In the past year, <PERSON> Willson </PERSON> has spoken across the country. At the scene of the accident 40 miles east of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, demonstrations, prayers, rallies and civil disobedience still elicit headlines, thanks to high-profile protesters such as the Rev. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Baez </PERSON>, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheen </PERSON>, author <PERSON> Alice </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> and peace activist <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellsberg </PERSON>. An ecumenical service will be held at the weapons station Thursday to mark the anniversary of <PERSON> Willson </PERSON>'s maiming. It will be the first time since June 10 that <PERSON> Willson </PERSON> has visited the spot where he inspires protesters but riles many of the 450 people in the adjacent town of <LOCATION> Clyde </LOCATION>, who have grown weary of the sight and sound of demonstrators on their doorstep. When demonstrators posted a handmade sign reading `` <PERSON> Brian </PERSON>,'' made to look like the town sign of `` Clyde'' across the road from the base gates, residents were outraged. The sign came down after a session with a county mediator. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Elam </PERSON> is typical of most townspeople today. He complains the protest site is an eyesore and demonstrators are `` left-wing radicals who sympathize with communist governments.'' The protesters meet with a wide range of responses. Earlier this week, 19-year-old <PERSON> Spaulding </PERSON> <PERSON> Brook </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> was leaning on the base fence near a sign reading `` Wage Peace'' when a man drove past, blared `` Boo'' through a megaphone and gestured obscenely. A carload of men yelled, `` Go home.'' Others driving by flash peace signs. The county has spent about $ 335,000 for patrols of <ORGANIZATION> Contra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Costa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sheriff </ORGANIZATION>'s deputies, who have arrested some 325 people since last Sept. 1, according to Sgt. <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Sizemore </PERSON>. Tired of the marathon protest and concerned about safe transportation of explosives across a 200-foot intersection, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> wants to build a $ 10 million overpass to takes vehicles over the highway, said base spokesman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Tikalsky </PERSON>. While the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> seeks funding from the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, others have turned to the courts. County prosecutors have failed to convict any protesters. <PERSON> Willson </PERSON> has sued the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and the crew of the train that refused to stop, and the crew has countersued. The Northern California chapter of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> sued to stop use of a painful choke hold on protesters being arrested. A federal court rejected a county request for permission to remove protesters' tables, chairs and picket signs from the edge of the highway. So the demonstrators remain, suffering occasional attacks with eggs, bottles and obscenities. <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodmacher </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Mount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diablo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in nearby <LOCATION> Walnut </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>, which helps coordinate the protests, says the local antagonism is ironic because, in 1986, voters only narrow