<HEAD>`World Monitor TV' Looks Beyond the Headlines</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 This will be an easy quiz. Two television newscasts, both inspired by newspapers, make their debut Monday. One show is based on <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Today </ORGANIZATION>, the other on the Christian Science Monitor. One show will cover international politics, the other will decide how we really feel about our bodies. Made the match? Even before they hit the air, it's obvious that `` World Monitor TV'' and `` USA Today: The Television Show'' will take dramatically different approaches to television news. _ Like the paper from which it springs, `` USA Today: The Television Show'' will be divided into four segments: news, money, sports and life. Each block will have its own anchor, and the emphasis throughout will be decidedly soft. _ Although the news philosophy of `` World Monitor TV'' is clearly more traditional, it looks to be the more problematic show. In an age where `` Entertainment Tonight'' succeeds as journalism and TV Guide is among the most-read magazines, straightforward reporting has come to be something of a gamble. Still, the makers of `` World Monitor TV'' are hopeful. Audiences, the show's creators suspect, may need a hard-news fix. `` People now who are addicted to information feel uninformed,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON>, the former <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> reporter who will serve as `` World Monitor TV's'' anchor. `` I want to know what's true about things. And I think most people do, too. If you leave people with a sense that the world is made up of unrelated fragments, I think you miss something. It's unbalanced.'' `` World Monitor TV'' will be broadcast weeknights at 4 p.m. and 10 p.m. -LRB- PDT -RRB- on cable television's all-documentary Discovery Channel, the fastest-growing cable network, with 32 million subscriber homes. `` I think the Discovery Channel's audience is very compatible with the kind of news program we want to produce,'' said <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, executive producer of `` World Monitor TV.'' The half-hour newscast, produced near the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monitor </ORGANIZATION>'s headquarters in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, will focus on only three or four stories each night and may remind viewers of public TV's MacNeil-Lehrer NewsHour, which uses a similar format The program will not, <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> said, make any effort to declare, `` That's the way it is.'' `` We have the luxury of not pretending to be a broadcast of record,'' <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> said. `` We're not going to chase every wisp of smoke. ... We are in the context business. That's our job. We can tell you what the news means. We can make connections, relate history. We can do the things you ca n't do when you're trying to hit all the bases. `` We'll use reporters and foreign correspondents who know the language and know the culture.'' While `` World Monitor TV'' will not be a video version of its newspaper cousin, the newscast will be supported by the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monitor </ORGANIZATION>'s 22 international and domestic news bureaus. Each broadcast will also include satellite-fed contributions from `` World Monitor TV's'' news desks in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hodding </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> will be the program's regular commentator. Do n't look for `` World Monitor TV'' to break news stories on a daily basis. That's not part of the plan, and the newscast does n't have the resources to support an investigative unit `` We might do a story on day care,'' <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said. `` And what we would do is look at the issue in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the Far East and <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. And then we would make comparisons. We're going to try to do things in depth.'' It is such thoroughness that drew <PERSON> Hart </PERSON>, a 28-year network news veteran, to `` World Monitor TV.'' `` At the networks, the commercial considerations are first,'' <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Hart </PERSON>, a Peabody Award-winning reporter, has also served as host of `` NBC Saturday Night News'' and `` NBC Sunday Night News.'' `` This place is a relief,'' <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> continued. `` Here, we wo n't make editorial decisions solely to garner an audience ... These people are interested in journalism. And that's it. They're not caught in the struggle between journalism and marketing. There's nothing wrong with marketing, but it pulls in the opposite direction _ toward fantasy, and not toward reality ... Here's a show where we can deal with ideas for a change.'' <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> calls `` World Monitor TV'' a `` modest proposal.'' He's right While `` USA Today: The Television Show'' has first-year start-up costs of $ 40 million and a staff of 160, `` World Monitor TV'' has been given $ 20 million for each of its first five years and has just more than 100 employees. Network news budgets, for contrast, averaged $ 275 million last year. `` USA Today: The Television Show,'' meanwhile, is banking that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> viewers want `` entertaining information,'' as the newscast is characterized by its producer <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON>, formerly of <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Today. <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON>'s show will be broadcast through syndication, appearing on more than 150 stations across the country. `` USA Today: The Television Show'' and `` World Monitor TV'' do have one thing in common: Neither will try to be a headline service. Each will try to complement, not compete with, the network newscasts. After that, however, all similarities between the two shows end. Thus, if you see `` World Monitor'' looking at the developing black middle class in <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>, expect `` USA Today: The Television Show'' to explain how men's and women's opinions of love differ. Which show will be a hit? That's hard to say. <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Today </ORGANIZATION>, the newspaper, has 5.4 million readers. The Christian Science Monitor's circulation, on the other hand, is less than 200,000 Sometimes, though, good things come in small packages.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Sept. 9-11</NOTE>
