<HEAD>Coming Election Will Determine Fate Of U.S. Free Trade Deal</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> has signaled the likelihood of a fall election to decide the fate of both the Canada-U.S. Free Trade Agreement and his Progressive Conservative government. In a heated three-way race, the landmark vote on <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s economic future would offer the nation a clear choice between conservatives, liberals and socialists <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> said in a Canadian <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> interview Sunday night, after keeping the country guessing for weeks, that he saw no reason to remain in office much longer than the traditional four years without a new election. Those four years end on Sept. 17. `` I've always believed that while the Constitution allows for a five-year term, that the custom of going about four years _ give or take a couple of months _ is a sound one, and it's one that should be respected,'' he said. An election call Sept. 17 would mean a mid-November election. Canadian campaigns normally last about eight weeks. If <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> wins, the world's two largest trading partners will proceed with plans to create a North American free trade zone on Jan. 1, eliminating all tariffs over 10 years and dismantling barriers to investment and competition. If he loses, both the main opposition <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the socialist <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> say they will tear up the complex trade deal hailed by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> as `` only a beginning'' in a global free flow of trade. <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>, 49, a former corporate lawyer who became leader of his party in 1983 and scored a landslide victory a year later, has been waiting for good omens before calling an election. But Liberal leader <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERS