ATION> 32 percent and <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> 30 percent. The latest Gallup Poll showed the Liberals with 35 percent, Conservatives 34 percent and <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> 30 percent. Small parties and independents took up the remainder. Such a tight race could result in a minority Conservative government lacking the votes to pass free trade. Historians compare the contest to the milestone election of 1911 when <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> Prime Minister Sir <PERSON> Wilfrid </PERSON> <PERSON> Laurier </PERSON> offered free trade but lost to Conservative <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Borden </PERSON> who pledged `` No truck nor trade with the <ORGANIZATION> Yankees </ORGANIZATION>.'' Despite presiding over a healthy economy and negotiating an accord to bring <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> back into the Constitution, <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> has struggled with a credibility problem referred to in the press as the `` sleaze factor.'' He lost eight Cabinet members in scandals ranging from tainted tuna to criminal charges. Liberals gloated this month when a disgruntled former <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> member from <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Suzanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Blais-Grenier </PERSON>, alleged the <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> government was operating `` a network of patronage and kickbacks.'' She gave no proof but the controversy swelled when two other Quebec Conservatives spoke of `` crumbs'' from the procurement table and information `` that could put a dozen people in jail,'' again without hard evidence. The other parties have their problems, too. Polls show Turner the most unpopular party leader, with only 15 percent voter approval. He has struggled for two years to even hold onto his job in a divided party and is embarrassed by <PERSON> Bourassa </PERSON>'s close links with <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>, whose government has pumped money into <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> Nearly two-thirds of voters say they like <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Broadbent </PERSON>, a former university teacher who claims to speak for `` ordinary Canadians.'' But his popularity may not translate into support for a left-wing party that has never governed <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and is committed to <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> withdrawal and protectionism.
