<HEAD>Leading Indicators, Factory Orders Down Sharply in July</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: grafs 1-8 new to UPDATE with factory orders; uppicks 5th graf
pvs: The departments ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The government said today its chief forecasting gauge of future economic activity dropped 0.8 percent in July, the sharpest decline in eight months, while orders to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> factories fell a steep 3.5 percent. Economists said the drop in the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Index of Leading Economic Indicators may be a signal of a pause in what has been booming economic growth this year. But they cautioned against reading too much into a single month's figures. The July decline was the biggest since last November, when the index dropped 1.0 percent in the wake of the October stock market crash. Orders for manufactured goods, which registered their steepest decrease in 18 months, were dragged down by a sharp decline in military orders, the department said. Orders for both durable and non-durable goods fell $ 7.9 billion last month to $ 220.2 billion. But the decline, the worst since a 3.6 percent drop in January 1987, had been anticipated. In a revision of the previous month's figure, the government said orders rose 5.4 percent in June, the largest monthly increase in more than 17 years. Both the stock and bond markets reacted cooly to the latest hints that the economy may be slowing. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s long bond was little changed, while trading was mixed on Wall Street. Separately, a government report released Monday showed a big drop in new-home sales last month in the face of higher mortgage rates. The departments of <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> said sales of new single-family homes fell 4.7 percent in July to a seasonally-adjusted annual rate of 686,000 units. It was the biggest decline since a 6.2 percent decline in December. The government also reduced estimates for June and May, showing less housing strength than previously believed. Fixed-rate mortgages have risen by almost a point since March to their highest levels of the year, boosting the monthly payment on a new $ 100,000 mortgage by about $ 65. But the housing report was well received by traders in the bond market, which has been languishing because of fears of inflation and higher interest rates. Bond prices posted the biggest gain in nearly four weeks, although trading was light. Brokers said lower commodity prices and a higher-valued dollar also played roles in the rally. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s key 30-year bond climbed nearly $ 10 per $ 1,000 face amount, its biggest one-day gain since Aug. 2. Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction from price, fell to 9.33 percent from 9.43 percent late Friday. The bond rally also helped Wall Street, which has been sensitive to rising interest rates. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which had bounced around last week to post a net gain of 1.43 points, rose 24.00 to 2,041.43.
</TEXT>
