<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Multimillionaire commodities trader <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON>, a legend whose luck turned sour after last October's stock market collapse, says he is leaving the futures business to concentrate on his other passion: politics. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON>, 39, known as the `` Prince of the Pit'' at <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s boisterous commodities exchanges, said Monday he was closing his accounts and selling his exchange seats so he could devote his energies to `` public policy and political endeavors. `` There is only so much satisfaction and utility to the making of money,'' <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> said in a prepared statement. He said he would use his personal fortune, reportedly around $ 200 million, as a launching pad for his new career. `` I am fortunate to have enough assets and opportunities to try to make a significant impact on our political lives. As I approach 40 years of age, I believe it is time for me to take on this new set of challenges,'' the statement read. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> said he would concentrate on writing, speaking and `` active involvement with voters and candidates.'' He was national co-chairman for the unsuccessful Democratic presidential campaign of former <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Babbitt </PERSON>. He also has made sizable contributions to several other Democratic campaigns since 1980, including the 1984 presidential bid of former Vice President <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> and the 1986 <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> gubernatorial campaign of <PERSON> Adlai </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevenson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> said he now supports the presidential bid of <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and has contributed $ 100,000 to his campaign. <PERSON> Babbitt </PERSON> believes <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> could have a large and lasting impact on the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. `` ` His primary concern is the power of ideas,'' <PERSON> Babbitt </PERSON> said. `` He wants to force the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> to rethink its agenda. He has a passion for economic reform.'' <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> also donated $ 10 million to establish the <ORGANIZATION> Roosevelt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, a liberal think-tank with offices in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, and is a leading financial backer of People for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Way </ORGANIZATION>, a liberal group formed as a counterpoint to the conservative Moral Majority. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON>, a native of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION>, began his financial career at age 17 as a $ 1.60-an-hour brokerage house runner at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. After graduating from <ORGANIZATION> DePaul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> with a degree in philosophy, he bought his first exchange seat _ on the tiny <ORGANIZATION> MidAmerica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> _ at age 21. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> owns seats on every major commodity exchange and runs two companies: C & amp; <ORGANIZATION> D </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodities </ORGANIZATION>, a futures trading partnership of which he is managing partner, and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, an advising firm for managed futures funds and accounts. His uncanny success as a trader earned him the nickname `` Prince of the Pit'' on the floors of the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. But his fortune seemed to sour after last October's markets collapse, in which C & amp; <ORGANIZATION> D </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodities </ORGANIZATION> reportedly lost $ 10 million. Two public commodity funds <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> launched last year in conjunction with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> also fell on hard times. After they lost more than 50 percent of their $ 115 million combined initial value, <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> suspended trading last April in the funds. Both funds resumed trading on Aug. 3 following a vote of confidence by investors, and each had lost about 3.5 percent when trading was halted for good on Friday, said <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Dennis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> spokeman. <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> blamed the losses on `` choppy markets _ the worst markets we've seen in 10 years.'' He said <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON>' decision to quit trading was not related to the funds' losses. Several veteran traders on the floor of the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON>' exit from the futures business had been expected. `` I know that for the last several years, his main interest in life has been politics, not trading,'' said <PERSON> Victo