<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> WINSTON-SALEM </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ A new smokeless cigarette developed by <ORGANIZATION> R.J. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tobacco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> will be test-marketed in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, beginning Oct. 1, company officials said today. The new cigarettes, called Premier, will be odorless and will generate only a trace of ash or smoke that could irritate people nearby, the officials said. Company officials said the new cigarettes contain a high-tech packet of tobacco extracts which is heated, but not burned. The price per pack will be about 30 cents higher than other cigarettes, said <PERSON> Betsy </PERSON> <PERSON> Annese </PERSON>, director of public relations for the Winston-Salem-based company. The company will use a variety of advertising messages to sell the new cigarettes, she said; one advertising approach will tout the new product as `` Premier _ the Cleaner Smoke.'' But the company is not making any health or safety claims. `` We're not claiming this is a safe or safer cigarette,'' she said. A health claim would invite regulation by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. `` If a product is sold with claims to make cigarettes safer, it is a medical device'' subject to <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> approval, said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Grigg </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. Anti-smoking groups are pressing the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> to regulate the new cigarettes as a drug because, they maintain, <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON> is making implied health claims for its product. In addition, the anti-smoking groups say the new cigarettes could appeal to teen-agers, thereby gaining a new generation of smokers as customers. Analysts said <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON> selected the test markets, in particular the <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> cities, because they have numerous older, sophisticated smokers who may be trying to quit smoking or are seeking an alternative.
