<NOTE>$adv 04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Sept. 3-4 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Russian Scare In American Wheat Fields</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL BATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WICHITA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A pinhead-sized aphid is giving new meaning to the words `` Russian menace'' as Midwestern farmers scout their fields for the insect. <PERSON> Leroy </PERSON> <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> entomologist, says the <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> wheat aphid is a crop pest that has been spreading since its discovery in <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> around 1900. It was in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> in 1978, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> by the early 1980s and crossed into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> in 1985 or 1986. `` It's relatively rare to find a pest that is a completely new pest to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, or in this case, the western hemisphere,'' <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> fields first were infested in April 1986. During 1988, at least 49 central and western counties were affected. As of July, the insect had spread almost to the Candian border and had been spotted in 14 states including <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Entomologists estimate the <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> wheat aphid has cost <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> small grains growers more than $ 100 million in insecticides and lost yields. Figures for the 1988 crop are n't yet available, nor are projections estimating the aphid problems the new crop might face. But in 1987, about 38 percent, or about 4 million acres, of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> wheat crop was affected, <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON> said. Infestation levels were even higher elsewhere. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> officials said all of their small grains crops were infested to varying degrees during 1987. In <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>, infestation was 64 percent and in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, 56 percent. In some cases, the aphids are present in enough numbers to kill plants, he said. Usually, their impact is on yields, turning potentially high yield fields into riskier ventures. The aphid also helps provide shelter for another pest, the greenbug. When Russian heat aphids attack wheat plant leaves, the leaves roll up. Greenbugs like the protection this affords and appear to use it for development, allowing them to attack in higher numbers, he said. Greenbugs and <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> wheat aphids are similar in appearance, <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON> said. The aphids have a more spindle-like body and do n't carry the dark stripe common to greenbugs The aphid also does n't have the visible cornicles, or tailpipes, the greenbug has, he said The first signs of Russian wheat aphid trouble come when plants begin to show a green and white streaked appearance on the upper side of their leaves, <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON> said. Damaged plants have a pink or purple cast to the undersides of their leaves, he said. Driving by a field is n't a good way to survey it for the aphids, nor is just checking the edges only. `` It is only when you get down on your hands and knees a ways into a field and start looking plant by plant and tiller by tiller that you can detect these early signs,'' <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON> said. He recommends checking about 20 consecutive plants and then doing the same at about five other spots in the field. Sometimes, wheat streak mosaic and other diseases or pests may mask the presence of the aphids, he said. Potential yields have to be taken into account when deciding whether to hire an aerial sprayer to apply insecticide for around $ 8 an acre. Volunteer wheat, which often sprouts after a harvest, and natural grasses make good hosts for the pests before they can prey on young planted wheat in early fall and early spring, <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON> said. Volunteer, which also can spread other pests and diseases, should be controlled to help eliminate problems. Some experts are recommending late-fall planting because early-planted wheat and small grains seem to suffer the worst aphid infestations. `` We really do n't have any good documented evidence on just how important that is right now,'' <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON> said. Entomologists fear the aphids could develop a tolerance to some of the insecticides now being used. `` Just a slight increase in tolerance could mean the difference between successful control and not being able to get control at all,'' <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON> said. Insecticide manufacturers are developing new chemicals that can replace those currently used if tolerance becomes a problem. Also, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> is conducting a study involving the importation of beneficial insects to control the aphid. Insects are being transported from <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> for the research work.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Sept. 3-4</NOTE>
