<FIRST>r f AM-Asia-Economy     08-30 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Asia-Economy,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Southeast Asian Influence Will Increase In World Economy, Think
Tank Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>'s role in the world economy will expand through the year 2000, while Japanese markets will become more competitive and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> output will decline, a think tank predicted Tuesday. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> on the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economy </ORGANIZATION> said in a long-range forecast that <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>'s Gross National Product, or its total output of goods and services, will rise steadily over the next decade while those of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will shrink. Through the turn of the century, <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>'s GNP will rise 5.4 points while GNP in the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> will decline 2.9 and 2.5 points, respectively, the institute predicted. Meanwhile, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s economy will grow at an average inflation-adjusted pace of 4.7 percent through the year 2000, the institute said. `` We have to be aware that the Japanese market will become increasingly competitive,'' the report said. `` This is because imports will continue to rise because of the yen's appreciation. `` The Japanese economy ... will be considered an extremely large market and direct investment by foreign companies will increase,'' it added. The institute said it based its prediction for the economic growth of <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> on the recent fast rise in trade among the countries in the region, including the so-called newly industrialized economies like <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> as well as among members of the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southeast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Asian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, including <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>. Steady development in the division of industrial production between <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> countries and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> will help avoid serious competition among themselves, the report said. Economic growth of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> has come primarily from the effects of policies set in motion, the report said, but the development of the <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> economy has drawn its strength from `` autonomous economic dynamism'' itself. The report forecast that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s economic growth will be powered by personal spending and private-sector capital investment. In addition, investment profits will surge in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, with the outstanding balance of investments in 2000 reaching $ 1.100 trillion and profits totaling at least $ 80 billion a year, the institute said. A characteristic of the Japanese economy toward the year 2000 will be clearly reflected in the country's international balance of payments, according to the think tank. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s trade surplus will shrink to $ 600 million from $ 94.3 billion in fiscal 1987 ended last March, almost attaining equilibrium, it said. Exports will increase an average 7.2 percent in each of the years but imports will register an 11.6 percent rise due in part to stronger internal demand for manufactured goods, the institute said. However, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> wo n't become a net debtor, according to the institute. The institute said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy has the potential to attain growth exceeding 3 percent a year after inflation is taken into account. `` Already, its trade deficit has been shrinking as a result of economic expansion led by exports,'' it said. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> budget deficit also will dwindle because of high tax revenues, it predicted. By the mid-1990s the so-called `` twin deficts'' will largely disappear, it said.
</TEXT>
