<FIRST>r f BC-Chevron-EPA     08-30 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Chevron-EPA,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Sues Chevron, Charging Benzene Leaks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The federal <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> is suing <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S.A. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, charging cancer-causing benzene is leaking from its refinery in south <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, the company announced Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> filed suit in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> here Monday accusing the gasoline giant of consistently failing over the past four years to monitor and repair the equipment that handles benzene at the refinery. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Galloway </PERSON>, spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> operations, said the company was in compliance with <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> regulations. <PERSON> Galloway </PERSON> said the company would cooperate with the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> on any problems that might have occurred. The suit seeks an injunction requiring the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco-based </LOCATION> corporation to comply with the federal Clean Air Act. `` Unless enjoined by an order of this court,'' the lawsuit says, `` these violations will continue.'' For each of the 19 alleged violations of the federal law, the suit seeks penalties of up to $ 25,000 a day. Neither the lawsuit nor government spokesmen gave a total dollar amount of possible fines. `` Benzene constitutes a serious health threat when released into the air. ... It is <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> policy to take whatever steps are necessary to ensure compliance with applicable emission standards,'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Seif </PERSON>, regional <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> administrator, said in a press release announcing the suit. Special Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smolski </PERSON> said it was unclear how much benzene had escaped from the refinery system because of the alleged violations. Different leaks have been occurring since 1984, he said. <PERSON> Galloway </PERSON> said that of 338 workers checked for benzene exposure in 1987, 98.3 percent were under <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> limits. He noted that the refinery is about 1 -LCB- miles from any homes.
</TEXT>
