<DOCNO> AP880830-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-88 1420EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     08-30 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0373</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stocks went nowhere today in what Wall Street brokers described as listless dog-day trading. `` There's really nothing going on. The floor is very quiet,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Eaton </PERSON>, a market strategist at <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. International in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, which rose 24 points Monday in some of the lightest trading this year, was up 0.53 point by 2 p.m. EDT to 2,041.96. Among broader market barometers, the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> composite index of all listed issues was up 0.14 to 148.69. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s market value index was down 0.46 to 294.59. Declining and advancing issues were about even on the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>, with 665 up, 653 down and 550 unchanged. Volume on the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> totaled only 74.47 million shares with two hours of business left. Brokers said <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reports released today that suggested the economy is slowing down, thereby easing fears of inflation, failed to induce much interest on Wall Street. The department said its chief forecasting gauge of future economic activity dropped 0.8 percent in July, the sharpest decline in eight months, and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> factory orders fell 3.5 percent. The figures were within expectations. Some brokers attributed the lack of business to pre-Labor Day vacationing. Others said professional investors were awaiting a more telling report on the economy's direction, the August unemployment data released Friday by the