<TEXT>
 The government said Tuesday its chief forecasting gauge of future economic activity suffered the steepest drop in eight months in July, but few analysts expect a substantial slackening in growth anytime soon. The 0.8 percent decline in the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Index of Leading Economic Indicators was the biggest since last November, when the index dropped 1.0 percent in the aftermath of the October stock market crash. However, economists noted that the index posted an exceptionally strong increase in June and cautioned against reading too much into a one-month downturn. In a separate report, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said orders to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> factories for manufactured goods plunged 3.5 percent in July, the worst decline in 18 months. But that drop followed a very strong showing in June and was heavily influenced by a wide swing in orders for military equipment. `` Despite the declines, we're not going to have any slowing in the imminent future,'' said <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The economy, as measured by the gross national product, grew at a 3.3 percent annual rate in the three months ended in June and at a 3.4 percent pace in the first quarter. <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> said this strong growth, which surprised many economists who had been anticipating a recession after the stock market crash, likely would continue through the July-September quarter. White House spokesman <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> with the vacationing President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, said, `` The data suggest continued economic growth in the months ahead, although at a more moderate pace than in the first half'' of the year. Barring something unforeseen, the economy could turn in its strongest performance since 1984. That would be good news for Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who is counting on a feeling of economic optimism among voters to bolster his chances of beatwk Quayle measures up. In eight years in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> has been known mostly f agan's Strategic Defense Initiative, his battle for the controversial federal court appointment of <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Manion </PERSON> and a losing fight against the 60-day notification for plant closings `` I do n't remember anything in particular,'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said, when asked if he had squared off against <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> on any other issues. And he makes repeated subtle references to <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s youth. `` I certainly do n't think he's too young but certainly you've got to have some maturity'' to be a heartbeat away from the presidency, he said at one <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> stop When reporters goaded <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> with questions on whether <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> would still be on the ticket Nov. 8, the Texan finally could n't resist. `` I hope so,'' he said. But away from the public eye, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> and his top aides are concerned about going into debate against <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> is younger than President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was when he won the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, but his face looks older, especially on television. The campaign has signed him up for coaching anD O\Llo he wo n't appear wooden whe ~ \ Oo And wxes years of consistent work, a te4zo -LRB- mecond bites. A well-briefu\m
