<HEAD>Drop in Defense Work Holds Down Factory Orders</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 2nd graf, ``The Commerce,'' to CORRECT figure to 3.5
percent, sted 3.4 percent</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY21</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Orders to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> factories for manufactured goods fell sharply in July, pulled down by the biggest drop in defense orders in more than four years, the government said Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said orders for both durable and non-durable goods slipped 3.5 percent to $ 220.2 billion last month. It was the worst drop since January 1987, when orders fell 3.6 percent. But economists were not concerned about the decrease because it was heavily influenced by the volatile military goods category and came one month after the strongest increase in total orders in more than 17 years. `` The orders numbers were down because of some fluctuations in some very volatile categories. They'll be up again in August,'' said <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. In July, defense orders plummeted 46.6 percent to $ 7.4 billion, reversing a 68.3 percent gain a month earlier. Last month's drop in this category was the steepest since April 1984. The June increase had been the biggest since December 1982. Excluding the defense category, orders were down 0.7 percent in July following a healthy 2.9 percent gain in June. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturing, which languished earlier in the decade because of the strong dollar, has rebounded. The weaker dollar has fueled a resurgence in sales of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> goods overseas and businesses have responded by spending more to upgrade and replace outmoded plant and equipment. But demand for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goods has been so strong that some analysts are concerned that factory capacity will be strained, pushing prices higher. <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kahan </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Kleinwort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, said that despite the overall drop in factory orders in July, `` there is very little evidence yet that the manufacturing sector is moderating.'' A particular sign of strength, he said, is the category of non-defense capital goods, which is considered a good indication of business expansion plans. It was up 0.9 percent to $ 35.8 billion, following a 12.5 percent increase in June. `` That, I think, is the more telling story. ... Despite the fact that last month's number was a strong increase, we were still able to scratch out a further increase this month,'' <PERSON> Kahan </PERSON> said. The overall July decline followed a 5.4 percent surge in June, the biggest since December 1970. Orders were down 0.3 percent in May. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> offered these details of July activity: _ Total orders for durable goods, `` big ticket'' items expected to last three or more years, were off 7.1 percent in July following an 8.7 percent gain in June _ Orders for transportation equipment, both military and non-military, were off 22.0 percent after soaring 33.3 percent a month earlier _ Non-electrical machinery was down 4.2 percent, while electrical machinery jumped 4.1 percent _ Orders for non-durable goods rose 1.0 percent after increasing 1.6 percent a month earlier _ Shipments of manufactured goods fell 0.9 percent to $ 216.9 billion, after rising 1.4 percent in June
