ember at $ 2.79 a bushel; oats were 5 cents to 8 \ cents higher with September at $ 2.54 -LCB- a bushel; soybeans were 14 -LCB- cents to 23 cents higher with September at $ 8.47 a bushel Precious metals futures drifted lower in quiet trading on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The inflation-sensitive metals were reacting to ideas that the economy is beginning to slow down, said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardillo </PERSON>, commodity futures trading adviser for <ORGANIZATION> Josephthal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. That view was bolstered by Tuesday's report of a 0.8 percent drop in the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Index of Leading Economic Indicators, the sharpest decline in eight months. Gold settled $ 1 to $ 1.60 lower with October at $ 431.90 a troy ounce; silver was 3 cents to 3.9 cents lower with September at $ 6.49 a troy ounce. Energy futures prices advanced on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in advance of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>'s weekly storage report, which analysts said was bullish for the market. The API reported <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil stocks dipped by 4.2 million barrels last week while distillate stocks fell by about 3 million barrels. Gasoline stocks rose by 699,000 barrels. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 5 cents to 13 cents higher with October at $ 15.27 a barrel; heating oil was .38 cent to .53 cent higher with September at 43.14 cents a gallon; unleaded gas