<HEAD>Georgia Power, Southern Co. Tax Accounting Investigated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Court papers unsealed Tuesday show federal agents are trying to determine if <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> avoided paying millions of dollars in federal taxes through the way it accounted for spare parts. Besides <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION>, one of the nation's richest utilities, the investigation includes its parent, the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, and the Big Eight accounting firm of <ORGANIZATION> Arthur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Andersen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co. The papers raise the question of whether the companies and their accountants sought to hide about $ 61 million in spare parts to avoid paying $ 50 million in federal taxes, interest and penalties. The complicated arrangement deals with whether parts are classified as being emergency spare parts or for maintenance and when they become expenses to the company. The papers also raise the question of <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION>'s accounting for the sale of 5 percent of Plant Vogtle nuclear power plant to the <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION>. In the documents, officials say the deal was treated as a sale of 5 percent of the $ 8.87 billion plant for book value purposes, but as 1.35 percent for tax purposes, saving the company between $ 10 million and $ 12 million. The papers include excerpts of taped conversations in which <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s tax chief agrees with a confidential informant that the company misled the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> over the tax accounting of the spare parts, but adds, `` Do n't ever say that.'' The investigation, which dates from 1982, is based largely on information contained in taped conversations between utility and <LOCATION> Andersen </LOCATION> officials and the informant, who is being paid for his participation and been exempted from prosecution, according to the court papers. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Barr </PERSON> confirmed the investigation, but refused to provide details beyond what was contained in the papers because a grand jury is involved. He said the investigation, which is continuing, involves possible criminal wrongdoing, including violations of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Tax Code. Although the court papers unsealed Tuesday focus on <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Andersen </PERSON>, <PERSON> Barr </PERSON> said other companies or individuals may be involved. The affidavit says Southern subsidiaries <ORGANIZATION> Mississippi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> used proper accounting procedures for spare parts. The Atlanta Constitution reported the investigation last week, after <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> agents executed search warrants at the downtown <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> headquarters of <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> as well as the home of <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Fallaw </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s director of taxes. The Constitution said other companies being investigated include <ORGANIZATION> Oglethorpe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which provides electricity to electric cooperatives in the state. In a Tuesday afternoon news conference, <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Scherer </PERSON> said the allegations `` if true -LRB- are -RRB- shocking to me personally and I'm sure to the employees of <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION>.'' <PERSON> Scherer </PERSON> said, `` I want to state as plainly as I can to you that I will not tolerate wrongdoing and I will not tolerate the coverup of wrongdoing at <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and I personally will get to the bottom of this matter.'' <PERSON> Scherer </PERSON> said the accounting for spare parts is `` one of those complex areas in the tax law that is open to legitimate disagreement among reputable accountants.'' The chairman refused to take questions. <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Gale </PERSON> <PERSON> Clappa </PERSON> said the holding company would have nothing further to add to <PERSON> Scherer </PERSON>'s statement. Officials at <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Andersen </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> office had no immediate comment on the material.
