<HEAD>Home Loan Mortgage Corp. OKs 4-1 Stock Split</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday approved a 4-for-1 stock swap as part of its plan to open up ownership of its preferred stock to public investors and bring a more than $ 1 billion windfall to the savings and loan industry. The corporation, known as <ORGANIZATION> Freddie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mac </ORGANIZATION>, is a congressionally created entity that buys home mortgages from savings institutions and other lenders and packages them into securities for resale to investors, making more money available for home buyers. Ownership of <ORGANIZATION> Freddie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mac </ORGANIZATION>'s 15 million preferred shares is currently restricted to the 2,500 savings institutions who are members of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> system. As part of an effort to bring new capital to the ailing industry, federal regulators in July voted in principle to lift restrictions on ownership of the preferred stock, which has no voting power. The price of the stock, which was $ 60 a share in early June, has soared. After Tuesday's announcment, spelling out details of how the ownership restrictions will be lifted, the stock rose $ 6.50 a share to $ 145 in trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, led by Sen. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Wis </LOCATION>., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, had been pressing federal regulators to funnel some of the windfall into the <O