<HEAD>Lower Price Drawing Higher Interest In Offshore Oil Lease Sale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN McGILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The federal government is scheduled to open Wednesday 371 bids made by oil companies hoping to snap up 270 tracts of bargain-priced oil properties in the western Gulf of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. It will be the third Gulf lease sale since the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> dropped the minimum per-acre price on the property from $ 150 to $ 25. And it's the second time western Gulf tracts are up for bids. Interest appeared high, with 93 companies qualifiying to bid. Eighty-four qualified for the central Gulf sale last March. However, when the number of bids actually was totaled Tuesday afternoon, it was far below the 931 bids received last March for the central Gulf properties. <PERSON> Eileen </PERSON> <PERSON> Angelico </PERSON>, spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minerals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said the number was down for two reasons First, the central Gulf waters are considered to be better oil properties. Second, the western gulf tracts were up for bids a year ago shortly after the minimum bids were lowered to $ 25 per acre. Almost 520 bids were received on the tracts then. The lower price is still seen as a means of boosting interest in the offshore tracts, <PERSON> Angelico </PERSON> said. `` We see it as an incentive to the smaller companies,'' she said. The western gulf territory covers about 5,080 underwater blocks covering about 27.9 million acres, mostly off the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> coast but some in deep waters off the <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> shore. <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> are both suffering economically from the domestic oil industry's depression and renewed interest in offshore leases was hailed as good news by industry representatives at the March sale. But a spokesman for one company cautions that the sale of more leases wo n't necessarily be followed by more drilling. `` That's driven more by other things,'' said <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Vehnekamp </PERSON>, public affairs manager for <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> office. The government gives the lease purchasers several years _ the number varies according to the type and location of the tract _ to exercise drilling rights, <PERSON> Vehnekamp </PERSON> said. Drilling costs, prices for the product and numerous other market factors come into play, he said. Bids will be opened beginning at 9 a.m. Wednesday at the <ORGANIZATION> Marriott </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION> in downtown <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>.
