<HEAD>Public Service of New Mexico Cutting 19.4 Percent Of Workforce</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE MAJOR HOLMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION> laid off 656 employees Tuesday, or 15.9 percent of its workforce, in the latest cutbacks under a major cost-cutting program. The state's largest utility had 4,126 full-time positions before the job eliminations. Tuesday's cuts boosted job eliminations to 19.4 percent of its workforce, and followed the layoffs of 129 union workers from <ORGANIZATION> PNM </ORGANIZATION>'s electrical operations and the elimination of all 14 jobs in its aviation department. `` Our goal is to have earnings such that we can continue dividends and regain our financial health,'' said <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Geist </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> PNM </ORGANIZATION> president and chairman. <PERSON> Geist </PERSON> said jobs were cut from operations across the state and from all levels of the company, including 30 percent reductions in the corporate office. He said the job cuts would save $ 28.4 million in salaries, wages and benefits a year and that non-labor cost-cutting measures would save $ 15.4 million. <ORGANIZATION> PNM </ORGANIZATION> officials also announced construction expenses were cut by $ 19 million in 1988 and $ 33.6 million in budgeted 1989 levels. <PERSON> Geist </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> PNM </ORGANIZATION> dropped its employee stock purchase plan and imposed an across-the-board salary freeze until the middle of next year. Executive salaries and benefits were cut in January, so the latest salary freeze is an extended freeze for <ORGANIZATION> PNM </ORGANIZATION> officials, he said. <PERSON> Geist </PERSON> said Tuesday actions would not affect the reliability or safety of electrical or gas service, but would slow the utility's response time for things such as requests for new service The utility's financial problems over the past year are largely due to a huge excess generating capacity. Its share of costs of the Palo Verde Nuclear Generating Station in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> and a unit of the coal-fired San Juan Generating Station near <LOCATION> Farmington </LOCATION> are not included in its rates. Earnings dropped 38 percent between 1986 and 1987 and have continued dropping this year, <PERSON> Geist </PERSON> said. Shareholder dividends have been cut by nearly 50 percent, he said. <ORGANIZATION> PNM </ORGANIZATION>'s stock, which climbed to a high of $ 39 in early 1987, rose $ 1.25 to $ 13.75 a share Tuesday on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>.
